<HEADLINE> Survey Says British Public Remain Hostile to EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A national referendum on
Britain's membership of the planned single European currency would
pose a serious political risk for the Labor government, according
to the Annual British Social Attitudes Survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, published in today's Financial Times newspaper,
revealed that some 61 percent of the British voters remained
firmly opposed to the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
This findings indicate that British Prime Minister Tony Blair
faces an uphill battle in persuading the British people of the
benefits of EMU, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Political commentators predict that the British government is
likely to hold a referendum on joining a single currency before
any decision was made.
</P>
<P>
A Financial Times report two weeks ago said the government
would shortly make a statement that sterling is likely to join EMU
soon after its 1999 launch sent stock and bond markets soaring.
</P>
<P>
However, British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown and
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook have both dismissed the report as
pure speculation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain's Liberal Democratic Party leader Paddy
Ashdown urged the government for a clear statement of intent on
the single currency as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"The declaration of intent should include a clear commitment to
joining EMU within a defined timescale -- say no later than the
end of 2001," Ashdown said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
