<HEADLINE> World Steel Consumption Forecast to Rise 4.5 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Global steel consumption will
grow by 4.5 percent in 1997 to reach a record 695 million tons
due to strong economic growth, according to a report published
today by the International Iron and Steel Institute.
</P>
<P>
The report said that demand is growing fastest in South
America, where it is likely to rise 12 percent this year, led by
growth in Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, economic recovery in western Europe will boost steel
demand there up 7.7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
As the recent drastic decline in steel consumption in the
former Soviet Union appears to have bottomed out, steel demand in
central and eastern Europe is forecast to grow by 4-5 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
It said that apart from increases of more than 10 percent in
steel consumption in Mexico and Canada, strong economic growth in
the US also adds to great steel demand in North America.
</P>
<P>
The report added that in Asia, growth in demand in China, South
Korea and China's Taiwan is offsetting a downturn in Japan and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that world steel use will continue growing steadily
by about 15 million tons a year in the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
