<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian-German Trade Increases: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The trade volume between Iran and
Germany amounted to 1.7 billion Marks (about 988 million
U.S. dollars) over the past five months despite U.S. embargo
against Iran, an Iranian trade official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Matthias Boddenberg, Managing Director of the Iran-Germany
Chamber of Industry and Commerce, said that Iran exported 500
million Marks (290 million dollars) worth of oil, fresh and dried
fruits and carpets to Germany in the period, while it imported
1.2 billion Marks (697 million dollars) worth of machinery,
equipment and raw materials from Germany.
</P>
<P>
The export of Iranian oil to Germany rose by 83 percent, and
that of fresh and dried fruits by 35 percent. But carpet exports
fell by 8 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
He termed the commercial relations between Iran and Germany
as being "friendly and based on mutual interests."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embargo against Iran has had no negative effect on
the relations between the two countries except for those companies
which are under influence of the United States, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the D'Amato Law signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton in
1996, the U.S. would impose sanctions on foreign companies
investing more than 40 million dollars in Iran or Libya. The
investment cap in Iran reduced earlier this year to 20 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
With regards to the extensive relations between Iran and
Germany, he said no other countries in the world are able to
replace Germany in its trade exchanges with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Iran's No. 1 trade partner. Iran's import from
Germany accounts for 15 percent of its total imports while export
to Germany makes up 5 percent of its total exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
