<HEADLINE> S. Leone Army Succeeds in Containing Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's Chief of
Defense Staff, Brigadier Samuel Koroma said today that his army
continues to "register successes in containing attacks from
Nigerian forces" stationed in the capital.
</P>
<P>
He did not give details about casualties, but said, "the cost
of human lives to the Sierra Leone fighters have so far been
minimal."
</P>
<P>
"The Nigerian forces are increasingly counting the costs in
skirmishes and even through the explosions of land mines they
planted at the (international) airport," he said in an interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
According to Koroma, the planted mines are made of plastic
which cannot be easily detected.
</P>
<P>
"They are located in places frequented by local farmers and
peasants who earn their living through subsistence agriculture,"
he claimed.
</P>
<P>
A military coup was staged on May 25 this year to oust the
civilian government of A. T. Kabbah and the 16-member Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) asked the Nigerian-led
west African peace keepers (ECOMOG) to force out the military
junta and reinstate the legitimate government of Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Koroma also accused Nigerian military pilots of using cluster
bombs on civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
"For them to use such bombs on targets in Freetown indicate
deep sinister purposes," he charged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
