<HEADLINE> London Tourism Conference Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A conference was told here today
that London in the future will be car free in the center, public
transport will be integrated and hotels will subject to compulsory
registration in order to enhance standards.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a London Tourist Board (LTB) conference -- London
Tourism the Millennium and Beyond, its chairman Sir John Egan
said, "By 2010 I want London to be the No. 1 destination for
business and leisure travel in the world."
</P>
<P>
Egan wanted to see 28 million visitors from overseas and 18
million from the rest of the UK coming to London and the industry
to generate 28 billion pounds (44.8 billion US dollars) for
London's economy in that year.
</P>
<P>
The conference was held to outline the LTB's vision for London
in 2010 and to launch the tourism strategy for London 1997-2000.
</P>
<P>
Chris Smith, secretary of state for culture, also speaking at
the conference, said, "London is vital to Britain's tourism
success. This is why the government has funded the LTB to run a
number of very successful overseas promotions."
</P>
<P>
London now attracts over 14 million visits from overseas and a
further 12 million from elsewhere in Britain. They spend in total
9 billion pounds (14.4 billion US dollars) and support a wide
variety of jobs across the capital, according to the LTB.
</P>
<P>
London's success means that other parts of the country also
benefit, the LTB added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
