<HEADLINE> African States Urged to Sign Land-mine Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Africa
International Affairs Representative (Saiar) declared October 6
to be Africa day of action against land mines and urged African
governments to sign the International Land-mine Ban Treaty this
December.
</P>
<P>
Saiar said in a statement issued here today that about 10
anti-land mine campaigners used the day to make correspondence,
congratulations and pleas to African governments to continue
their stance on land mines.
</P>
<P>
''Campaigners also urge governments to work to bring the
international ban treaty into force before the year 2000,
increase de-mining activities and release funds for victim
assistance,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
One of the activists, former Mozambican first lady Graca
Machel wrote letters to African leaders, saying she was proud of
the way in which they supported land-mine ban during the
negotiations for the land-mine ban treaty in Oslo last month.
</P>
<P>
The Saiar urged the Democratic Republic of Congo, Egypt,
Eritrea, Liberia, Nigeria and Sierra Leone which were not
represented in Oslo to give up the use of land mines.
</P>
<P>
The statement said African members of the Commonwealth which
would meet in Edinburgh, Scotland, from October 24 to 26 should
urge their partners to sign the treaty.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the United States to sign the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from many countries will meet in Ottawa,
Canada, in December this year to sign the treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
