<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Vote for Electoral Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Botswana's citizens have
voted in favor of amending the country's constitution to allow
for electoral reforms, according to sources reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
In a public vote on Sunday, 59 percent voters supported
lowering the voting age to 18 from 21 years old, 73 percent to
establish an independent electoral commission and 70 percent to
allow Botswana's citizen outside the country to vote, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
A fourth amendment to the constitution, that the president
shall serve only two terms of five years, was recently approved
by Botswana parliament, and will not be subject to a referendum.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has had only two presidents, the late Sir Seretse
Khama, who died in office after serving for 14 years, and
Ketumile Masire, who has been in power for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Although there is wide speculation that Masire, 72, will step
down before 1999, the constitutional amendment is not retroactive
and he will be allowed to serve a further two five-year terms if
his party maintains its majority, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
