<HEADLINE> Talks to End S. Leone Crisis to be Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Renewed talks to end the
current political impasse in Sierra Leone will begin in Abidjan,
Cote d'Ivoire Thursday, state house aides told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
According to the aides, the Sierra Leone delegation will leave
Freetown Wednesday and will take with them proposals for "a quick
solution" to finding a peaceful resolution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Initial talks broke down in July after military strong-man
Major Johnny Paul Koroma announced in state radio and television
he would return democratic rule to the west African state in four
years' time.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in the capital said delegates representing
the ousted civilian government will travel from Guinea, where
they are in exile, to the meeting, which has been called by the
committee of five on Sierra Leone, namely Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire,
Guinea, Nigeria and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The daily Expo Times newspaper, which normally mirrors the
views of the military government, said in an editorial today, "We
think the junta should be ready to make concessions and go along
with the wishes of the international community which might mean
well."
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria is gradually, if not speedily becoming one of the
stake-holders in our crisis," the paper continued.
</P>
<P>
"The Nigerians now have two hostages (ousted President Tejan)
Kabbah and detained rebel leader Foday Sankoh. Kabbah and the
junta should now start talking to each other indirectly through
ECOWAS-5."
</P>
<P>
The junta has repeatedly called for the formation of a
national unity government to solve the crisis in Sierra Leone,
which has been rejected by both ECOWAS (Economic Community of
West African States) leaders and the ousted civilian government,
saying constitutional rule should be returned to the civilian
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
