<HEADLINE> Soldiers, Ex-rebels Clash in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Clashes broke out between
soldiers and former rebels at the weekend in eastern Sierra
Leone, leaving 16 fighters seriously wounded, a report reaching
here said today.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses and local journalists were quoted by two
independent radio stations as saying that regular army soldiers
and fighters of the People's Army were mining for diamonds at a
site known as "open eye" near Togo when the fight erupted on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Security forces had to intervene to end the fighting, which
prompted many civilians to flee, and reinforcements were sent on
Sunday, a military spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
No one was killed in the clash but 10 soldiers and six former
rebels were seriously wounded, he added.
</P>
<P>
The People's Army is made up of the ex-rebel Revolutionary
United Front which fought against successive governments of the
country since March 1991 and now in principle allied with the
junta that ousted the legitimate government in a coup in May this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
