<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thapa Appointed Nepal's New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra tonight
named Surya Bahadur Thapa as the country's new prime minister
while the outgoing Lokendra Bahadur Chand demanded that Thapa and
his followers be stripped of parliament membership for violating
the law.
</P>
<P>
With support from the Nepali Congress (NC), Nepal Sadbhavana
Party (NSP) and two independents, Thapa, president of the National
Democratic Party (RPP) and prime minister for five times between
1964 and 1983, garnered a majority of 107 votes in the Lower House
to stake his claim for the premiership, according to a communique
issued by the king's Principal Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution of this Himalayan kingdom, a minimum of
103 votes is needed to claim the post of prime minister in the
event that no single party holds an outright majority in the
205-member Lower House.
</P>
<P>
After the mid-term election in late 1994, no single party
commands a majority in the Lower House and coalition politics has
thus emerged in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Thapa's coalition government will first be one between the RPP
and NSP before the NC joins later, sources said.
</P>
<P>
This government must win a vote of confidence in the Lower
House within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chand has written to the king and the speaker of the
Lower House respectively, accusing Thapa and his followers of
violating the Anti-Defection Act, an informed source said.
</P>
<P>
Under the act, MPs risk losing their seat in the parliament if
they vote against the party whip.
</P>
<P>
Before the Lower House voted on the NC-tabled no-confidence
motion against the Chand-led government, Thapa and 14 other RPP
MPs held a parliamentary party meeting in the absence of Chand,
their parliamentary party leader, and decided to vote for the
censure motion, leading to the fall of the government on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In his letters, Chand demanded that those MPs voting against
its own government be stripped of their parliament membership, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
But the Anti-Defection Act also provides that MPs will not be
considered defecting when joining a party formed by 40 percent of
either the party's working committee members or the parliamentary
party committee members.
</P>
<P>
Thapa now has two-thirds of the RPP Lower House members on his
side.
</P>
<P>
"In no circumstance will our party split," Thapa claimed one
day after Chand resigned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
