<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third African Land-use Workshop Opens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A month-long third African
community-based land-use planning workshop for rural development
started today in Masvingo, south Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The workshop being attended by 27 participants from 13 African
countries is aimed at promoting the sustainable use of natural
resources for agricultural and rural development.
</P>
<P>
At a opening ceremony, Masvingo provincial Governor Josaya
Hungwe said African countries should put more emphasis on
land-use planning which involves participation of the community
if meaningful development is to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He stressed conscientization and participation of the
community on resource management and environmental issues was an
important product of land use planning for rural communities.
</P>
<P>
Hungwe said, ''the development of an articulate expression of
community interests is more strategic than the physical
development of the land and its resources.''
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, he said, policy makers had put emphasis on
land-use planning involving the community for visualization of
resource management plans in a dynamic manner.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that land-use planning was the only way to
reduce ''negative'' land-uses.
</P>
<P>
''Today we live in situations where every piece of land has
multiple uses. This is more so with the communally managed
land,'' Hungwe said.
</P>
<P>
The governor said, ''through the process of land-use planning
we hope to reduce mutual negative impacts of different land uses
to a minimum.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
