<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Tons of Illegal Weapons Destroyed in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Twenty tons of confiscated
illegal firearms worth more than 2 million Rand (420,000 U.S.
Dollars) were destroyed in Pretoria today, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi and Police
Commissioner George Fivaz watched as the first of 4,504 pieces of
weapons were crushed and melted at 1,600 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
"By destroying these arms, we are making certain that they
will never again be recirculated in our community," Mufamadi
said.
</P>
<P>
The weapons destroyed today included pistols, revolvers,
rifles, shotguns and homemade arms. They were confiscated by
police during countrywide investigations.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the availability of firearms to criminals
created fear among communities.
</P>
<P>
"It is a matter of extreme importance and priority to strictly
control legal arms and to stem the flow of illegal firearms into
the country," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The South African Police Service was committed to stopping
illegal arms being brought across South Africa's borders.
</P>
<P>
To this end, joint operations with Mozambican police had
resulted in the destruction of several tons of firearms and
ammunition over the past two year, Mufamadi said.
</P>
<P>
During the last operation in August and September this year,
more than 100 tons of firearms and ammunition were destroyed in
northern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Andrew Lesch said another 4,500 illegal arms
are awaiting destruction.
</P>
<P>
Firearms played a crucial role in South Africa's seemingly
endless waves of violence. Incidents of armed robbery, rape and
shootings were reported almost every day across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
