<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Nepali New Prime Minister Thapa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Surya Bahadur Thapa, one of
Nepal's old timers in the premiership, was named again tonight by
King Birendra to head the country's next government.
</P>
<P>
Born into a landlord family in eastern Nepal on March 21, 1928,
 Thapa graduated from Allahabad University, India.
</P>
<P>
He began his political career in 1950 by participating in the
underground student movement. He joined the Nepali Congress (NC)
in 1954 and four years later, he was elected chairman of the Royal
Advisory Assembly.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 31, Thapa was elected into the Upper House of the
Nepali Parliament.
</P>
<P>
In 1960, he was appointed minister for agriculture, forest and
industry before becoming minister for finance and economic affairs
in 1962 and minister for finance, economic planning, law and
justice the following year.
</P>
<P>
From 1964 to 1983, he served as prime minister five times
including as chairman of the Council of Ministers (cabinet) from
1964 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
He suffered a setback in his political career in 1972 when he
was arrested under the country's Security Act and had been
imprisoned until 1974.
</P>
<P>
Thapa founded the National Democratic Party (RPP) in May 1990
and merged his party with the RPP (Chand) in January 1992. He has
since been president of the RPP.
</P>
<P>
He believes that democracy cannot flourish without proper
protection of nationalism, human values and human dignity in a
liberal environment.
</P>
<P>
His sole hobby is reading while his recreation is gardening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Refugees Return from Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 100 Somali refugees
today reached the southern port town of Kismayu, 500 km south of
the capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kismayu said the refugees who stayed in camps
inside Kenya have voluntarily returned back home.
</P>
<P>
VHF field radio reports in Kismayu said the refugees who
looked very weak, tired and malnourished complained about
insecurity and what is characterized as mistreatment by the
Kenyan police force in the camps.
</P>
<P>
They had also protested against scarcity of medicine and lack
of proper education for their children.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that the Bajun community, one of the Somali
unarmed ethnic clans living in middle and lower Jubba regions
have forwarded a letter to the United Nations High Commission for
Refugee (UNHCR), complaining about a repatriation plan by the
agency for nearly 3,500 Bajun refugees in camps in the Kenyan
coastal town of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Local elders from the Bajun community in Kismayu said they
asked UNHCR to delay its plans for the repatriation since their
home islands near Kismayu -- Kudhayow, Jula and Jawaia -- lack
the basic facilities needed for the existence of human being.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bajuns, there are no adequate potable water
and shelter in these islands. The elders furthermore said they
have invited the UNHCR to send an assessment team to visit these
islands before the repatriation takes place.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, 95 Somali refugees have returned to Mogadishu from
Mombasa on commercial ferries that docked at the natural port of
El-Ma'an, 30 km north of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The refugees who arrived on two different ferries in the past
two weeks said they have not been deported or repatriated, but
have returned back home voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
The refugees who did not receive any welcome from anybody
complained about the recent insecurity in Mombasa, saying they
feared for their lives and preferred to come back to Mogadishu
from where they ran away about six years ago at the height of the
civil war in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a committee for the business community in Mogadishu
have appealed to people in the capital to refrain from all kinds
of activities that might add to the already insecure atmosphere
there.
</P>
<P>
The business committee have made their appeal at a time when
the high seas have ended and the natural ports are beginning
their normal activities.
</P>
<P>
The call by the business committee also came at a time when
some sub-clans living in south Mogadishu have been busy in
looting vehicles from one another for retaliatory reasons. The
public transport buses in several areas in the capital have been
scarce following the fear of looting by the bus owners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
