<HEADLINE> UK Public to Be Questioned on Womens' Fighting Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The British public are to be
asked whether they approve of women serving in frontline combat
roles in an opinion poll to be launched by the Ministry of Defense
(MoD).
</P>
<P>
British Defense Secretary George Robertson is expected to make
an announcement about opening up more jobs for women in the three
services during a Commons defense committee at the start of the
parliamentary session.
</P>
<P>
Before a final decision was made, Robertson and Armed Forces
minister John Reed, both of whom are keen to expand equal
opportunities in the Armed Forces, have decided to ask the public
for their views.
</P>
<P>
An MoD report said, "Apart from being the quickest and cheapest
method, this approach carried the advantage that the questions
would be included among a wide range of other questions on
non-defense issues and would therefore be less likely to attract
public attention."
</P>
<P>
Women already serve widely within the Armed Forces, including
front-line RAF aircraft and on board Royal Navy ships, but they
have not been allowed to serve in the front line roles in the
Army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
