<HEADLINE> Irish FM Resigns Amid Allegations Against Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Irish Foreign Minister Ray Burke
resigned from parliament early today amid allegations against him,
according to reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Burke, who has been accused of accepting a 30,000 Irish punt
(about 43,700 U.S. dollar) political donation from an Irish
businessman in 1989, tendered his resignation following fresh
controversy over the granting of passports to an Arab banker in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Burke, who is co-chairman of crucial all-party Northern Ireland
peace talks, was reported to have authorized naturalization
certificates under a legal "passports for investment scheme" in
return for a promised investment of 20 million punts (about 29
million dollars) in job-creation.
</P>
<P>
Opposition political parties have been pressing for Burke's
resignation, saying the recent allegations against him have
undermined his credibility in the Northern Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old government minister was quoted as saying that
he had been a victim of the smear campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
