<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ease of Mideast Crisis to Help Doha Summit: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has expressed hope for the ease in the Middle East crisis
to help the controversial Middle East and North Africa Economic
Summit achieve its goals.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks at a meeting with Secretary-General of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Jamil Al-Hujailan in the United
Nations headquarters in New York Monday night, a statement by
Riyadh-based GCC secretariat said today. The statement gave no
details of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief hoped that the ease of the Mideast crisis will
encourage Arab states to attend the gathering scheduled in
November in Doha, Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The annual event, launched in 1994 and held last year in
Egypt, is traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel and
their major trade partners in the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
But a deadlocked Middle East peace process has soured the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Several Arab countries including Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates have announced their intention to boycott the
summit in line with the Arab League's decision to suspend
normalization with Israel following Israel's construction of a
new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The 22-member Arab League decided last month to let its
members to decide for themselves whether to take part in the
meeting or not.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has expressed time and again its resolve to host the
annual economic meeting, but its Minister of State for Foreign
Affairs Ahmed Abdullah al-Mahmoud announced recently that the
conference would be downgraded to the level of foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"Qatar's decision to organize the conference was adopted in
the light of progress in the peace process," the minister of
state was reported as saying.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met the foreign
ministers of the GCC states in Saudi Arabia trying to persuade
these countries to take part in the summit during her Middle East
tour last month.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates,
Qatar, Oman and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
