<HEADLINE> Egypt Opens Advanced Military Information Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt opened a military
information center here today, describing it as the "most advanced
specialized one" in the Middle East, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak inaugurated the center as part
of the country's celebrations of the 1973 October War with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Defense Hussein Tantawi also attended the
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak gave the go-ahead for military news dissemination on
the Internet, which will present subscribers with accurate and
reliable information on the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The computerized center have access to various information
sources and decision-making bodies at home and abroad, according
to MENA.
</P>
<P>
Besides providing information on Egypt's armed forces, the
center will follow up news through 39 radio stations, 35 TV
channels, eight news agencies, the Internet and the Arab and
foreign press.
</P>
<P>
The new establishment will analyze news in regard to national
security, military affairs, disasters, crisis, national
development and terrorism, MENA said.
</P>
<P>
The 1973 October war was launched by Egyptian troops to recover
territories including the Sinai Peninsula captured by Israel in
the Six-Day War in June 1967.
</P>
<P>
The war ended after an 18-day fighting and a ceasefire
agreement was reached between Egypt and Israel. Egypt recovered
the Sinai Peninsula under U.S.-brokered disengagement agreements
in 1974 and 1975. In 1979, Egypt signed a peace treaty with
Israel, becoming the first Arab country to conceive peace with the
Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
