<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Urge Implementation of Water Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Wang Bingqian, vice-chairman of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, has
called for the intensive implementation of the Water Law in a bid
to make a sustainable use of limited water resources in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang said China should vigorously battle flooding, water
pollution and wasted water resources in accordance with the
law. However, he also noted that remarkable achievements have been
made in water conservancy construction and the protection of water
resources since the law went into effect in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Wang, leader of a fact-finding group looking at implementation
of the law, made the remarks today at Changsha, capital of central
China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Results of the tour will be fully considered in future
revisions of the law, according to Yang Zhenhuai, a member of the
NPC Standing Committee and co-chairman of the NPC Environmental
and Resources Protection Committee.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the Water Law centers on the exploration, use and
protection of water resources, as well as the protection of water
conservancy projects, management of water usage and flood
prevention projects.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned 11-day fact-finding mission is being carried
out around the Dongting Lake, the second largest lake in China,
which holds some 30-40 percent of annual floodwaters from the
Yangtze River. The area is a crucial flood prevention and
protection area in the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
Both the central and provincial governments have invested
heavily in water conservancy construction in order to form flood
prevention, power generation and irrigation networks in recent
years, according to Hunan Governor Yang Zhengwu.
</P>
<P>
However, the lake area is still vulnerable to annual flooding
due to the limited capacity for floodwater discharge. 
</P>
