<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Optimistic About Economy: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are feeling good about
the country's economic prospects, according to a new poll
published today.
</P>
<P>
Half of those surveyed by Angus Reid Group Inc. said they
expected the national economy to improve in the next year.
</P>
<P>
It was the highest-level of optimism the polling firm has
recorded since it began asking the question a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
"Thinking about the next year or so, do you yourself generally
feel that the Canadian economy will improve, stay about the same,
or get worse," the poll asked.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, 50 percent of the respondents said they think the
economy will strengthen in the next 12 months, compared with 12
percent who said things will get worse and 37 percent who expected
no change.
</P>
<P>
The 50-percent reading is up from 45 percent in a July survey
and 39 percent in a January poll.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that optimism is more prevalent among
men, university-educated people and the affluent.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the mood of Canadian consumers has been
improving steadily since January 1996, when pessimists outnumbered
optimists by a two-to-one margin.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey of 1,503 people was conducted on September
23-30. It is considered to be accurate within 2.5 percentage
points 95 percent of the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
