<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Web Sites Don't Boost Sales: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Few North American retailers are
making money from their Internet investments, according to a new
study published today.
</P>
<P>
North American retailers are pouring an average of roughly
20,000 U.S. dollars into setting up their Web sites, but they
expect little payoff in the way of increased sales.
</P>
<P>
"Until the typical middle-aged consumer feels comfortable with
this burgeoning technology, adoption rates in most retail
categories will remain low and various retail applications will be
restricted," the study said.
</P>
<P>
"Like many technological innovations, it may take a generation
for Internet shopping to attain mainstream status," it added.
</P>
<P>
However, retailers who ignore the Internet do so at their own
peril, warned the study, which was done by the Toronto-based
Polytechnic University's Center for the Study of Commercial
Activity.
</P>
<P>
By 2005, large chunks of some retail sectors will have to set
up shop on the Internet, according to Prof. Ken Jones, who
co-authored the study.
</P>
<P>
But a big stumbling block is money, he said. The cost of
experiments and the uncertainties of adoption have created many
barriers to entry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
