<HEADLINE> China Says It Will Further Combat Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China today told a U.N. conference
on desertification that it will join hands with other countries in
the fight against desertification.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Guangyao, head of a Chinese delegation to the first session
of the Conference of Parties to the U.N. Convention to Combat
Desertification (CCD), said here that "extensive and effective
international cooperation" is needed to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
Zhu called on the developed countries to actively transfer
advanced technology to developing countries to help with their
fight against desertification.
</P>
<P>
"The developing countries should also intensify scientific
research and training to combat desertification and try to get
their own people mobilized in the fight," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu went on to say that China, as one of the countries worst
affected by desertification, is willing to cooperate with other
countries to combat desertification and make its own contribution
to the implementation of the CCD.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification,
designed to curb degradation of arid lands affecting more than 1
billion people worldwide, was adopted in June 1994 and went into
force in December 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
