<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weakening Peso Forces Manila to Defer Corn Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine National Food
Authority (NFA) has decided to temporarily shelve the importation
of 300,000 metric tons of corn because of an increasing world
market price of corn caused by the weakening Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the NFA told the Philippine News Agency today that
the peso depreciation plus the 35 percent tariff to be imposed on
this corn importation has resulted in higher landed cost.
</P>
<P>
They said the landed cost of corn is already at 8 pesos (22
U.S. cents) per kilo while the domestic wholesale price for the
commodity is only 7 pesos per kilo. Farm-gate prices are just more
than 6 pesos during the corn harvest season in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the landed cost is still higher than the existing
domestic prices, the country's corn users are now hesitant to
commit to buy the imported corn, they said.
</P>
<P>
The importation of the 300,000 metric tons of corn was approved
by President Fidel Ramos last month to prevent an expected corn
shortage resulting from a severe drought due to the El Nino
weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Weathermen have forecast that El Nino will hit the Philippines
from late this year to mid-1998 and will lead to a severe drought
in the country.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a large-scale oceanographic and meteorological
phenomenon that develops in the Pacific Ocean. It can cause
extreme climatic variability such as devastating rains, winds and
drought.
</P>
<P>
The peso today depreciated to as low as 35.537 against the U.S.
dollar at the local currency market, a 34.6-percent drop in its
value in two and half months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Gene Sequencing Center to Open in Vancouver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada is planning to open a
center next year in Vancouver to research on the genes of people
with breast, prostate, colon and lung cancer, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Chemist Michael Smith, a Nobel laureate, will head up the new
genome sequencing center.
</P>
<P>
"There is no institution like this in Canada... Canada would
really have been left behind if we were not getting into this
field," Dr. Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Gene sequencing involves analysis of DNA structure and the
exact order of the molecules in the DNA.
</P>
<P>
The order is considered important in understanding the cause of
disease. When the order of the molecules is altered, mutations
that lead to disease can sometimes develop.
</P>
<P>
Canada has research programs that hunt for genes and other
programs that extract information about DNA.
</P>
<P>
But until now, its scientists have been forced to leave the
country to pursue research in genome sequencing involving humans.
</P>
<P>
The new center will try to bring back Canadian scientists who
are now working in other countries as well as provide facilities
for those educated in Canada, Dr. Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Gene sequencing research is currently undertaken in labs in the
United States, Britain, Japan, France and Germany, according to
the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Smith said that the new center will not be duplicating work
done at other centers. Instead, it will deal specifically with
cancer-related issues.
</P>
<P>
It will focus on types of cancer in which it is possible to
follow the disease from early to advanced stages, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
