<HEADLINE> Roundup: Israel, Jordan Ties Soured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu expressed his readiness Monday night to mend
the relationship with Jordan, soured over the assassination
attempt by Israeli agents on a Hamas leader in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Two men holding fake Canadian passports attacked the political
chief of Palestinian Islamic movement Hamas Khaled Mashaal on
September 25 in the Jordanian capital. The two assailants were
arrested by the police, who uncovered that they were sent by the
Israeli intelligence service Mossad to assassinate Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan, who has been a close ally of Israel
among the Arab countries, blamed the attack as a "reckless
act...carried out by a party with no faith in peace." He reportedly
told his confidants that he had come to the brink of breaking ties
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is one of
the two Arab countries that have diplomatic relationship with the
Jewish state besides Egypt. King Hussein mediated the Hebron
accord between the Palestinians and Israel in January this year
and has been carrying out cooperation with Israel since the
normalization of their bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In an immediate effort to calm the fury of Hussein and to mend
the relations, a high-ranking Israeli delegation, including
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon and security officials, was dispatched to
Amman on September 28 to negotiate for the return of the two
agents.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein publicly called on Israel on September 30 to
release the jailed Hamas founder and spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed
Yassin. On the next day, Yassin was set free by Israel and flown to
Amman in a Jordanian airplane, believed to be under a deal between
Jordan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath, 11 Palestinians and nine Jordanians were
released by Israel after Jordan set free the two Israeli agents
who got home in obscurity, in sharp contrast with the hero's
welcome received by Yassin upon his return to his home town of
Gaza on Monday.
</P>
<P>
So far, the issue of assassination attempt by the Israeli
agents has come to a conclusion for the time being, but diplomats
here argue that the gap between Jordan and Israel is not so easy
to be bridged. It is understood that distrust, especially on the
part of Jordan, has cast a shadow over the bilateral relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler-Benz to Switch to Euro in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest industrial group
Daimler-Benz AG today announced its support for the European Union
(EU)'s plans to introduce the single European currency, the Euro,
as the "corporate currency" from its planned start-up date of
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under a decision made today by the board of management of
Daimler-Benz, the Euro would replace the German mark as the
company's standard monetary unit for all relevant business
transactions from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The board also decided that the company's business results for
the first half of 1999 are to be drawn up in Euro. Its customers
would also be able to choose Euro or their national currency to
pay their bills on a voluntary basis during the transition period
of the Euro from 1999 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision is basically a signal for our customers,
suppliers and partners in industry and public administration that
we see a tremendous chance both for Europe and our group in the
European Monetary Union," said Daimler-Benz Chairman Juergen
Schrempp.
</P>
<P>
Under the Euro timetable, the conversion to the single currency
would not be compulsory in its member states until January 2002,
when the Euro banknotes and coins would be officially introduced
after a three-year transition period during which the Euro would
only be used in cashless transactions.
</P>
<P>
By deciding to convert to the Euro as early as January 1999,
Daimler-Benz is one of the first German companies to take such a
step at this early stage.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz Chief Financial Officer Manfred Gentz estimated
the company's costs for the currency conversion at about 200
million marks (114 million U.S. dollars), with more than half of
the money used for the requisite adjustments to data processing
within the group.
</P>
<P>
However, the Euro introduction would also cut the company's
currency exposure by about 30 percent, thus largely eliminating
performance risks from unforeseeable exchange-rate fluctuation,
Gentz said.
</P>
<P>
"This would yield greater security for corporate planning, in
turn considerably enhancing the operating conditions for the
individual business units," Gentz added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Warned Against Tomahawk Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The former head of the U.S.
strategic nuclear forces, General Lee Butler, today warned that
any move by Australia to purchase Tomahawk cruise missiles could
spark a regional arms race.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of such a weapon into Southeast Asia is
unlikely to go unanswered by Australia's neighbors, Butler said
when answering a question at Canberra's National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
"My experience in 33 years is that if nations view you as a
threat, equally as you do them, they will never concede to you an
advantage they consider strategic," he said.
</P>
<P>
Australian Defense Minister Ian McLachlan confirmed in August
that the country was considering purchasing the long-range
missiles, used with devastating effect in the Gulf War against
Iraq, the Australian Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The missiles, with a range of 1,500 kilometers, could be fitted
to Australia's F-111 strike bombers or new Collins class
submarines.
</P>
<P>
Australia's consideration of the weapons has already been
criticized by New Zealand's opposition Labor Party which has
warned that such a purchase would place defense ties between the
two countries under considerable strain.
</P>
<P>
Butler advised that a series of questions have to be asked
before considering such a purchase.
</P>
<P>
"What are the threats to Australia?" he asked.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
