<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechnya Ready to Issue Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chechen Republic, which has
been struggling for complete independence from Russia, is ready to
issue its own passports, the Itar-Tass new agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ruslan Alikhadzhiev, speaker of the Chechen parliament, who
announced this move in an interview with the Itar-Tass in Grozny,
said more than half a million Chechen citizens will receive their
new passports.
</P>
<P>
As for the fact that the republic has not been recognized by
the international community as a sovereign state, and the new
passports can cause inconvenience when their holders go outside
the republic, the speaker said, "If the international community
does not recognize our passports, we shall not ask them for this."
</P>
<P>
The Chechen leader also said that Chechnya had dispatched 200
samples of new passports to various countries so that their
officials would have an idea of new Chechen documents.
</P>
<P>
Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov has noted that he did not
want Chechen citizens to have passports with Russian symbols.
</P>
<P>
"We shall have our own Chechen passports with a Chechen coat of
arms," he said in a televised speech.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov issued a statement Monday to reaffirm Chechnya's
further drive to develop interstate relations with Russia. He
complained that the sour relations between Chechnya and Russia had
aggravated recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
