<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Support for Separation Drops in Quebec: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Support for separation in
Canada's French-speaking province of Quebec has dropped to its
lowest levels in three years, according to a new poll published
today.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Post/Campas poll found that only 41 percent of
Quebecers now back the province's seccession from Canada.
</P>
<P>
That compares with the 48.5 percent who supported separation at
the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
When asked "Do you want Quebec to separate from Canada and
become an independent country?", 23 percent of the respondents
said that they would definitely vote yes, 18 percent probably yes,
13 percent probably no and 46 percent definitely no.
</P>
<P>
And for the first time in several years, definite no voters
outnumbered definite yes voters by a 2:1 margin.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 500 Quebecers was conducted October 1 to October
3. It has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.5 percent, 19
times out of 20.
</P>
<P>
Despite an apparent softening of support for Quebec's
separatist movement, its leaders remains one of the most popular
politicians in the province.
</P>
<P>
Its leader Lucien Bouchard was popular second only to federal
Progressive Conservative leader Jean Charest, while Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien was a distant third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
