<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Fund Indigenous People in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government with all
major players in the tourism industry is looking into ways to
establish a revolving fund to assist indigenous people interested
in tourism, The Herald daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Public relations manager for the Zimbabwe Tourism Authority
(ZTA) Lesley Gwindi yesterday said most indigenous people who
wanted to venture into the industry did not have enough capital.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of potential in the tourism industry but
indigenous people have not been able to utilize it because of
lack of funding. We have agreed to set up a revolving fund and we
are now looking into ways of sourcing for funds," said Gwindi.
</P>
<P>
Although tourism is one of the fastest growing industries in
the country, only a few indigenous people are actively involved
in it. Last year Zimbabwe earned about three billion Zimbabwe
Dollars (about 250 million U.S. Dollars) from tourism.
</P>
<P>
Over 150,000 people are directly employed in the tourism
industry. Expansion of the industry would result in more jobs
being created.
</P>
<P>
To increase indigenous participation, the ZTA recently carried
out a tourism investment project to identify community leaders
countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Several viable projects were identified by the teams and ZTA
is now helping them to source funds and implement the projects.
</P>
<P>
The ZTA also will hold tourism development conference in
Harare at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be attended by tourism practitioners of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Gwindi said millions of dollars would be needed to fund
indigenous tourism projects which have already been identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
