<HEADLINE> Kim Urges to Solve Korea-US Auto Dispute Through Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam today instructed his government to solve the auto
trade dispute with the United States through "dialogue and
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"It is not desirable to emotionally react to the U.S. decision
to invoke Super 301 provision against South Korea's auto
industry," said the president. "We should make a cool-headed
judgement on what is in our national interest."
</P>
<P>
Increased trade friction with the nation's largest trade
partner would not benefit either country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president issued the instructions after receiving a report
on the ongoing South Korea-U.S. auto trade dispute from Trade
Minister Lim Chang-yul.
</P>
<P>
"I want the government to do its best to solve the problem
through dialogue and negotiations," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
However, Kim asked the minister not to accept any undue and
excessive demands from Washington.
</P>
<P>
South Korea should make it clear to the U.S. side that it
would never accept any demands beyond international standards, Kim
said.
</P>
<P>
Kim also instructed his government to bring the case to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) and take other steps to defend his
country's national interests provided the U.S. takes any
unilateral action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
