<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Trades More With Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia imports and exports more
from and to other developing countries than developed ones, shows
statistics in the latest Least Developed Country Report based on
data of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The developing countries continue to be Zambia's major source
of imports, accounting for 54 percent of its total imports with
the rest from the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is the second major source of Zambia's
imports, accounting for about 26 percent, while Japan supplies
about 8.6 percent, United States and Canada about eight percent
totally.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's imports from East Europe are very minimal amounting
to only 0.3 percent of its requirements.
</P>
<P>
In terms of exports, Zambia heavily relies on the developing
countries, accounting for 61 percent of its total exports while
the remaining exports go to the developed ones.
</P>
<P>
The European Union accounts for 16 percent, Japan 17 percent
and the United States and Canada only 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's imports reached 64.8 million U.S. Dollars at the end
of July this year, compared with 63.3 million Dollars at the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Its exports stood at 762 million Dollars in the corresponding
period compared to 638 million Dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Party Aims to Bring Down Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor
Party has set up two new committees to probe into a embarrassing
fiasco of Israeli intelligence service Mossad in Jordan and to
bring down the hardline Likud government.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jerusalem Post today, Labor chairman Ehud
Barak declared the establishment of the committees on Monday, of
which one will personally target Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and the other mount a parliamentary campaign for the downfall of
his government.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the second committee will be charged with the task
of initiating contacts with all coalition parties to convince them
to leave the government.
</P>
<P>
Labor Knesset (parliament) member Dalia Itzik blamed Netanyahu
for not qualifying for the prime ministership, saying that "All
gloves are off. Netanyahu will not be able to escape us any
more."
</P>
<P>
"We will not let him rest. We will expose him morning and
night for what he truly is - a danger to the nation and to the
security of its citizens," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition Meretz Party leader Yossi Sarid asked the
Knesset subcommittee for secret service to investigate the role of
Arthur Finkelstein, Netanyahu's electoral campaign adviser, in his
national decision-making.
</P>
<P>
"Each time the government hits a crisis, Netanyahu calls in
Finkelstein to advise him instead of calling on someone from the
defense establishment," Sarid complained.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "the problem lies with the prime minister.
Netanyahu is a serious security hazard. He is not suitable as a
prime minister. His decision-making is defective and deficient."
</P>
<P>
Two Mossad agents were arrested by Jordanian police after they
failed to assassinate Hamas leader Khaled Mashaal in Jordan's
capital Amman on September 25. The incident led to a secret deal
on swap of prisoners and the release of founder of Hamas Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin and his return to home town Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
After the two agents were freed and back home, Netanyahu
declared to set up a three-member committee, which will be chaired
by Yosef Ciechanover, a former legal advisor of the Defense
Ministry, to investigate the failed attack.
</P>
<P>
But security sources said this three person committee has no
legal authority and only a official state commission of inquiry
would have sufficient authority to determine the truth and draw
appropriate conclusion.
</P>
<P>
They also voiced the fear that Hamas would be strengthened by
the Mossad failure and that it will step up terror activities
against Israel in order to press for the release of more Hamas
prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy, Mordechai meet Ross on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said here today that the resumption of peace talks between
Israelis and Palestinians is an important step toward reviving the
stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Levy said this during his meeting with the U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross, who arrived here on Monday to help reopen the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
The two exchanged views on how to ensure the effective
negotiations of several Israeli-Palestinian committees appointed
to work out their respective agendas at their sessions from today
on.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also met Ross here
today.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Mordechai told Ross that the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has began to fight terrorism and the Israeli side
hopes that the PNA continues to fight terror in the future.
</P>
<P>
Ross met Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu this
morning and is scheduled to meet him again. The U.S. envoy will go
to Ramallah, West Bank to meet PNA President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks came back to life here last
night at a meeting of Levy, Ross and the PNA negotiator Mahmoud
Abbas, which brought a commitment to renewing cooperation in all
spheres, including security.
</P>
<P>
Intensive negotiations are expected next week in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
