<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Moves to Limit Damage After Tourist Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia's new federal Tourism
Minister Andrew Thomson today moved to limit damage to the
multi-million dollar Japanese tourist trade from the murder of a
young Japanese tourist in northern Queensland, Northeast
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Thomson, who was appointed earlier this week following Prime
Minister John Howard's ministerial reshuffle and has yet to be
sworn in, said however that he did not think the murder was
racially motivated and that it would probably have no impact on
the number of Japanese tourists visiting northern Queensland.
</P>
<P>
"Economic factors have a much bigger influence on the number of
tourists than isolated incidents of this kind," he said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese tourist Michiko Okuyama, 22, went missing in Cairns
late last month and her body was found naked and covered by palm
fronds and leaves on October 4 in the Cairns Central Swamp in
suburban Manunda, about two kilometers northwest of Cairns.
</P>
<P>
Her disappearance and murder have been widely publicized in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
As police interviewed a juvenile and examined what they
believed to have been the murder scene, the Japanese-speaking
tourism minister conducted interviews with Japanese reporters who
were in Cairns to cover the story and asked them not to overreact
to the murder, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Japan is an important tourism market for Australia. More than
600,000 Japanese tourists visited Australia in 1995-96 with 77
percent of them going to the state of Queensland, whose tourism
industry ranks first among Australia's six states or territories.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
