<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Wheat Exports Hit All-Time High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia's wheat exports
smashed a decade-long record this harvest season to post an
all-time high of 19 million tons, the Australian Wheat Board (AWB)
said today.
</P>
<P>
The 19 million tons of exports loaded on 750 ships in the
harvest year to September 30, 1997, broke the previous record of
15.9 million tons set in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the harvest, in the four months between
December 1996 and April 1997, a record average of 2.2 million tons
of wheat exports were shipped from Australia.
</P>
<P>
AWB General Manager International Nigel Officer said the export
figures were an endorsement of Australia's integrated marketing
system.
</P>
<P>
Officer said that based on the benchmark Australian Standard
White 10 pool return, about 3.2 billion U.S. dollars in export
revenue is expected to flow back to growers from the 1996/97
harvest.
</P>
<P>
He said cooperation between grain handlers, waterfront unions,
rail and transport providers and the growers enabled the AWB to
achieve the record outcomes.
</P>
<P>
"We delivered on time every time and this has enhanced
Australia's reputation as a reliable international supplier."
</P>
</TEXT>
