<HEADLINE> Europeans Cautioned on Taiwan Official's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Shen
Guofang today cautioned Western European nations that they will
risk relations with China by allowing Lian Chan, a Taiwan
official, to visit those countries.
</P>
<P>
"China strongly demands that concerned European countries will
proceed in line with their friendly relations with China and will
not allow Lian Chan to engage in any activities. Otherwise said
countries will cause serious consequences to their bilateral
relations with China," according to Shen.
</P>
<P>
"Should concerned countries allow Lian Chan to visit,
regardless of excuses or format adopted, the nature will be
serious, and it will constitute interference in China's internal
affairs," said Shen.
</P>
<P>
He warned that "China will have to respond strongly."
</P>
<P>
Shen made the remarks during a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that Lian Chan's attempts to go to some European
countries under the pretext of travel or vacation is aimed at
creating "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" and sabotaging
friendly relations between China and European countries,"
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly opposed to such actions," said Shen.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Taiwan issue is a crucial issue of
principle concerning the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
China, and the reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Shen noted that Taiwan is an inseparable part of China, and
stressed that the government of the People's Republic of China is
the only legitimate government representing the nation.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that China firmly opposes the Taiwan authorities'
efforts to carry out international activities designed to split
the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
