<HEADLINE> S. Africa Not to Lobby for UN Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today that his country is interested in
a permanent seat in the United Nations Security Council, but it
would not lobby other countries for the position.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral in Cape
Town, Mandela also avoided backing India's bid for a permanent seat,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"These are questions we will agree on at the appropriate time,"
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Although the majority of the 185 member states of the United
Nations agree that the UN Security Council should undergo reform,
they could not agree on how to reform it.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that the expansion of the UN Security
Council would be a long process that would definitely involve enormous
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council has five permanent members -- Britain,
China, France, Russia, United States -- and 10 non-permanent members,
half of which are replaced every two years.
</P>
<P>
Gujral arrived in Johannesburg on Sunday night. He flew to Cape
Town for talks with Mandela, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to address parliament this afternoon, and will
attend a banquet in his honor hosted by Mandela later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
