<HEADLINE> Indonesian Firms Fined for Fishing in Aussie Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Two Indonesian fishing
companies, which were convicted today of "illegally" fishing in
Australian waters, have paid 1 million Australian dollars (720,000
U.S. dollars) to have their fishing boats returned, the local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Northern Territory's Foreign Fishing Operations
Unit, Col Mellon, said the owners of 10 other Indonesian fishing
boats caught illegally fishing in Australian waters in the last
three weeks would also stand trial soon, the Australian Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
He said a change of wind direction was one of the main reasons
for the recent increase in the number of Indonesian fishing boats
in Australian waters.
</P>
<P>
Mellon said the 720,000 U.S. dollar payout for the four boats
as well as their equipment and catch is far from a record amount.
</P>
<P>
He said in the past 4.2 million U.S. dollars had been paid for
the return of one fishing boat.
</P>
<P>
Mellon also said that even though the number of Indonesian
boats "intruding" into Australian waters has increased lately many
people are exaggerating the problem.
</P>
<P>
"People have become alarmist because they think we are being
invaded. Well we are not. These are just fishermen."
</P>
<P>
But he did say the problem of illegal foreign fishermen in
Australian waters is "huge" and needs constant vigilance by units
such as his.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign fishing operation units, funded by the federal
government's Australian Fisheries Management Authority, are
positioned at strategic points all along Australia's coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
