<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Expert Urges Punishment of Unfaithful Husbands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A family expert in Macao has urged
legal departments to take measures to punish unfaithful husbands
as the cases have increased rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Su Yuk Lien, an expert with the family service department of
the Macao Charity, told the local Tai Chung Pou newspaper that her
department has received more than 600 such complaints from women
this year, compared with only over 300 last year.
</P>
<P>
"Certain departments of the government should take actions,"
she was quoted as saying, "so that the problem will not
deteriorate."
</P>
<P>
She said many women began to seek help from her department
since early last year, and because most of the cases involve
couples living together without marriage certificates, her
department could offer little help.
</P>
<P>
Most of the women seeking help were of lower-income family, and
they had to live on their husbands' income. They said they had
great difficulty in their daily life, in their children's
education and housing, after their husbands left them and started
a new family elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Once the problem occurred, she said, there was narrow chance
that the couple renew their relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Such problems cannot be overlooked," she said. "Only when the
unfaithful husbands get punishment can such problems be stopped
from further spreading." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Stage Military Maneuvers in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced today that it is
to stage grand military maneuvers in the Persian Gulf amid reports
that the U.S. orders its aircraft carrier Nimitz to rush to the
region.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Ali Shamkhani told a press conference that the
war games will cover a 50,000-square-kilometer area in the
northern section of the Gulf "up to the Kuwaiti border."
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani said some 50 Iranian destroyers and vessels, two
Russian-made Kilo-class submarines, 100 speed boats and 18
aircraft will take part in the two-week-long maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, following the most massive drill which ended
late last month in Qom, some 100 kilometers south of capital
Tehran, are scheduled to begin on October 9.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani said that different branches of the Iranian armed
forces will take part in the maneuvers in order to "create
coordination and bring about a common operation language."
</P>
<P>
He said the war games will involve the ground, naval and air
forces of the regular army as well as the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps, the main and largest fighting force formed by
Iranian government after it came to power in the 1979 Islamic
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came only days after the U.S. aircraft carrier
Nimitz, carrying 50 warplanes, was ordered to gear up toward the
Gulf. Pantagon has warned Iran that its aircraft are in danger of
being shot down if they violate an allied-imposed ban on flights
over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On September 29, Iranian warplanes struck a rebel base inside
Iraq, 170 kilometers southeast of Baghdad. The base is within the
no flight zone designated by the U.S. to prevent Iraqi attacks on
Iraqi Shiite rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
