<HEADLINE> Two German Managers on Trial for Exporting Technology to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Two German managers stood trial
today in the western German city of Moenchengladbach on charges of
illegally exporting poison gas production facilities to Libya, the
German news agency DPA reported.
</P>
<P>
The two men, aged 48 and 55, were accused of smuggling
facilities for the production of lethal poison gas to Libya via
Belgium in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Having been in custody for more than one year, the two had
denied the accusations and argued that they had no idea of how to
use the equipment.
</P>
<P>
The Moenchengladbach trial was the fourth one since 1990
concerning illegal German exports of poison gas technology to Arab
countries, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In two previous trials, two convicted German managers was
sentenced to five years, and four years and three months in jail
respectively. 
</P>
