<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Monks Gather for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- About 800 monks from all over
Sri Lanka gathered here this afternoon to show their support for
the peace process initiated by the government.
</P>
<P>
Under the scorching sun, the monks sat around a Buddha statue
in the Viharamahadevi Park and prayed for peace. Many of them came
from Trincomalee, Batticaloa and other places, where Tamil rebels
are fighting with government troops.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 bystanders joined the prayer and some of the
supporters distributed leaflets to passersby. On walls near the
park, stickers read: "Stop the brutal war."
</P>
<P>
One senior monk in a speech said: "All the nation should get
together, all people should live as brothers as the Lord Buddha
had taught."
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist monks blessed an undivided country which, while
retaining its integrity, will provide a peaceful settlement to the
present ethnic war so that all communities could live in an
atmosphere of peace, unity and harmony in one country.
</P>
<P>
They described the peace package of the government as the only
way to peace.
</P>
<P>
However, their view is not shared by some other Buddhist monks.
In the very same park, a sit-in demonstration was held on
September 30 by some 200 monks to express their opposition to the
peace process of the government.
</P>
<P>
The monks said the devolution package, put forward by President
Chandrika Kumaratunga, was aimed at satisfying the Tamil
extremists and therefore they would not support it.
</P>
<P>
Though the government is making every effort to push through
the devolution package and bring peace to the war-torn island,
some major obstacles exist.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said it would be very difficult for the
government to push through the proposals if it cannot gain support
from the Buddhist monks as Buddhism is quite influential in Sri
Lanka's social affairs and politics.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has
already rejected the devolution proposals. It seems the rebels
will continue their war with the government to gain independence
in the north and east of the country, where the Tamils make up
almost two-thirds of the total population with the Sinhalese
accounting for only 13.2 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
