<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Jobless Edging Toward 4.5 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of jobless people in
Germany rose by a seasonally adjusted 34,000 to 4.497 million in
September, the German Federal Labor Office said today.
</P>
<P>
The increase was higher than the 25,000 expected earlier by
analysts.
</P>
<P>
Although unadjusted figures showed the jobless dropped from
4.327 million in August to 4.308 million in September, that still
represented an increase of 459,600 since September last year.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate, based on unadjusted data, fell to 11.2
percent in September compared with 11.4 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
Bernhard Jagoda, president of the labor office, said he was
disappointed by the latest figures. "Unfortunately, we still have
to wait for an improvement on the job market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Peter Hausmann today also admitted that
the current economic upswing in Germany was still not good enough
to bring a turnaround on the job market.
</P>
<P>
It remained a top political priority to combat unemployment, to
create new competitive jobs and to prepare Germany as a production
base for the next century, Hausmann said.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates by the German business daily the
Handelsblatt, Germany would face an average unemployment of 4.45
million in 1997, which would be 150,000 more than foreseen by the
current government budget and would incur an additional 7.5
billion mark (4.3 billion U.S. dollar) financial burden.
</P>
<P>
The huge cost of unemployment benefits is a major drawback to
Germany's efforts to meet the fiscal qualification for the planned
single European currency, the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
