expressed increased optimism over Hong Kong's future after the
handover, according to results of a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey was commissioned by the Hong Kong Federation of
Youth Groups and conducted from September 8 to 24. About 44
percent of the 547 respondents aged between 15 and 29 said they
had more confidence in the future.
</P>
<P>
A total of 62.7 percent said they were confident the "one
country, two systems" policy would be fully implemented in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of the respondents had no criticism of the
policies Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa had implemented since the
handover, but 13.2 percent were "very unhappy" with his policies
on social welfare and livelihood. 
