<HEADLINE> More Schools Operating in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 7 (Xinhua ) -- Mozambican Education Minister
Arnaldo Nhavoto said that the number of primary schools, from
grade one to grade five, in the country would rise from 5,689 to
6,050 next year.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that 96.7 percent of the schools destroyed in
the war will resume operation, Nhavoto said Monday at a meeting
sponsored by his ministry, according to the local paper, Noticias
today.
</P>
<P>
He said the registered pupils will grow to 1.9 million next
year from this year's 1.74 million.
</P>
<P>
The number of schools with grade six to seven will rise from
the present 337 to 381 next year, with the students in these
grades rising from 1.5 million to 1.77 million, Nhavoto said.
</P>
<P>
Schools with grade eight to ten will grow from the current 63
to 70 next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are now 6,343 students at their grade 11 to
12 study from 5,158 last year.
</P>
<P>
There are about 7,500 people studying at five colleges in the
country with a total population of 18 million people, he said.
</P>
