<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's flagcarrier,
Cathay Pacific Airways, says it will continue with plans to accept
delivery of 10 new planes next year although it has called this
year as its "worst year in decades".
</P>
<P>
"We are not canceling any of our orders for next year," deputy
managing director Philip Chen was quoted as saying in today's
South China Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
The report said the company has four Boeing 777-300 aircraft,
five A340-300s and one A330-300 on order.
</P>
<P>
Last week Cathay managing director David Turnbull warned staff
the airline faced tough times because of its "appalling" passenger
 loads. Outside factors such as a fall in Japanese business and
the depreciation of Southeast Asian currencies had hurt the
airline this year.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the number of passengers began in the
summer. Rather than growing, Cathay's year-on-year monthly totals
started to fall, by 12 percent in June and 13 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
"We still have a sound balance sheet, thanks to the many years
of being prudent," he said, adding that in this business a
long-term view should be taken.
</P>
<P>
Cathay's main advertising push was outside Hong Kong because
other markets contributed 80 percent of its revenues.  
</P>
