<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Rate Down Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Federal Ministry of
Finance announced Monday that the country's inflation rate
dropped to 13.5 percent in August, 1.5 percent lower than the
government's target for this year.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate of Nigeria has been kept sliding since last
year, mainly due to the government's tight fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1995, the inflation rate was as high as 72.8
percent. It went down to 28 percent a year later and stood at 26
percent at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
By last June, it had dropped to 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government projected that the figure for September would
be 12.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government's effort in bringing down the inflation has
been commended by most observers. "Prices are very stable now and
this means people can buy." One of them was quoted by This Day as
saying.
</P>
<P>
But according to this newspaper, some analysts are doubtful if
the figures reflect the realities on ground.
</P>
<P>
They argue that the inflation rate is down simply because the
government refuses to release the budgetary money to critical
segments of the economy and the ordinary people have virtually
lost the financial muscle to buy essential goods.
</P>
<P>
They are worried about the embarrassing level of inventories
at the warehouses of many companies and poor manufacturing
capacity utilization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
