<HEADLINE> Support for S. African Ruling Party Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) has won its support in Western
Cape Province to a position where it could challenge the
white-dominated National Party in an election, according to a
poll by the Institute for Democracy in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that declared voting intention for the ANC had
stabilized nationally at roughly the same level as 1994,
recovering to 54 percent from a low in last November of 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Party has suffered major erosions in
five provinces, the poll said, noting that the support for the
white party in the critically important battleground of the
Western Cape province has dropped from 41 percent to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is administratively divided into nine provinces.
</P>
<P>
Bob Mattes, who announced the result of the poll, said that
all the political parties in South Africa had lost support.
</P>
<P>
"ANC identification among blacks had dropped from 75 percent
to 51 percent" while the National Party's white support had
fallen from 48 percent to 19 percent, he said.  
</P>
