<HEADLINE> Macao, Guangdong Police to Launch Joint Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Police departments in Macao and
south China's Guangdong Province will launch a joint exercise
against illegal immigration Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The joint exercise will be conducted at the sea between Macao
and Zhuhai City, which adjoins. Police forces from Macao and
Guangdong Province, with dozens of vehicles and ships, will try to
stop illegal immigrants from escaping the mainland and entering
Macao.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong police departments will mobilize about 1,500 people
posed as "illegal immigrants" for the joint action, and Macao
security police forces will also increase patrols in the bordering
area.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the Macao Maritime Police Department said
that the joint exercise was decided in July at a regular meeting
between police departments of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The exercise is intended to enhance the cooperation between the
two sides in the fight against unlawful activities, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
Police in Guangdong have conducted a series of anti-illegal
immigration exercises over the past few months following Hong
Kong's return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The number of illegal immigrants entering Macao was fewer than
380 over the past few months, a drop of about 200 compared with
the average number last year. 
</P>
