Bank of Australia (RBA) gathered for its October meeting to
consider monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Financial markets have been speculating that the central bank
might cut the official cash rate, which now stands at 5.0 percent
in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 72.30 U.S. cents down from
72.77 previously.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is looking forward to tomorrow morning because that
is the first opportunity for the RBA to cut rates," said IBJ
senior exchange manager Shane Spurway.
</P>
<P>
The next opportunities for the cut are seen after the labor
force data Thursday, and after the third quarter inflation and
wages data due for release on October 22 and 23 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The labor force figures due Thursday are expected to show total
employment jumped by a seasonally adjusted 42,500 in September
reversing a 38,200 fall in August.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 88.14 down from 88.71 against
the Japanese yen and at 1.2689 down from 1.2794 against the German
mark.  
