<HEADLINE> Iraqi Delegation in Beirut for Rapprochement with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A Iraqi trade delegation, first
since 1994, is in Beirut for talks with Lebanese officials on ways
to boost bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The 14-member delegation, headed by Adnan Qudsi, chairman of
Iraq's chamber of commerce, which arrived here on Monday on a
six-day visit, has met with Lebanese Economy and Trade Minister
Yassin Jaber, Minister of State for Finance Fouad Seniora and
Industry Minister Nadim Salem.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Yassin Jaber, Qudsi said that he was
here to "beef up commercial and economic ties", Lebanese newspaper
the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was traditionally one of Lebanon's leading trading
partners, accounting for 20 percent of exports of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, diplomatic ties were severed after the 1994 killing
in Beirut of an Iraqi dissident. And the political controversy
erupted again two months ago as Iraqi athletes were barred
from the Pan Arab Games held in Beirut under the pressure
from other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Jaber played down the possibility of restoration of diplomatic
ties, saying "At the moment it's a matter of economic ties only."
</P>
<P>
"The Lebanese will have to be patient. Iraq is a major market
in the region and a good outlet for Lebanese industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the head of the Beirut Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Adnan Qassar told the newspaper that contacts between the Lebanese
and Iraqis will only lead to private arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he was advocating breaking the sanctions on Iraq, he
responded, "Maybe. Dubai is doing it. So are the Jordanians, the
Turks and the Egyptians."
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is doing it, so why should Lebanon be left out?" he
added.
</P>
<P>
A Lebanese industrial fair is scheduled to be held in Baghdad
between October 13 and 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
