<HEADLINE> Parliamentary Task Force to Probe Into Albania Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Assembly of Albania
today approved launching a parliamentary task force to probe into
the turmoil that devastated the country early this year.
</P>
<P>
The special commission, to have 11 members, would review the
series of events leading to the widespread unrest across the
country in the first few months of the year, said a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
At a parliamentary session tonight, some representatives
suggested the task force analyze the roles and workings of the
state intelligence, presidency and armed forces at the time.
</P>
<P>
They expected the investigators to determine whether the
initial demonstrations were normal responses to the political and
economic tensions then or part of a premediated armed rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil, during which over 2,000 Albanians were killed or
injured and 1,200 arms depots looted, was believed to be triggered
by the failure of shoddy get-rich-quick pyramid investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
It led to international intervention into this tiny Balkan
nation with troops deployment and the resignation of the
government then. A general election was held June 29 ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
A proposal for kicking off a parliamentary investigation was
raised by some legislators and then went through parliamentary
President Skender Gjinushi and all parliamentary groups.
</P>
<P>
Gjinushi also consulted parliamentary committees in charge of
public order and intelligence operations before submitting the
plan to the floor of the People's Assembly, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Diversion Canal Open To Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Navigation started on a 3.5-km
long diversion canal on the southern bank of China's Yangtze
River in the morning of October 6.
</P>
<P>
All ships will have to use the canal to pass the Three Gorges
Area in the river's middle reaches. The main course of the river
is now closed to navigation and will be cut off by two parallel
cofferdams for work on a 2,335-meter-long Three Gorges Dam.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze is the world's third longest river. It is navigable
for 2,800 km and accounts for 70 percent of China's inland
navigation, hauling 80 percent of the country's goods that go by
waterways.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that by the year 2000, there will be 15.5
million tons of goods going via the Three Gorges Dam annually and
2.5 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
The construction work for the whole project is in three
stages. During the first, from 1993 to 1997, workers have
completed building a water diversion canal and other work. It will
be completed with the blocking of the main stream in early
November.
</P>
<P>
The second stage will be from November to the year 2003, with
work on the big dam itself and its numerous generator
rooms. During this period, ships will use the man-made canal with
the help of a temporary ship lock on the northern bank. The start
of generating electricity will mark the end of the second stage.
</P>
<P>
The third stage will be from 2004 to 2009, when the man-made
canal is cut, the permanent ship lock finished, by 2003, and ships
will use it.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the Three Gorges Dam will improve navigation
conditions on the 660-km section in Sichuan province because 100
dangerous shoals will be covered by a huge reservoir.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
