<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Events: Yassin's Release and Swap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Following is a chronology of
events concerning Israel's release of Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed
Yassin and his return to homeland Gaza in exchange for Jordan's
freeing of two Israeli agents captured in the failed assassination
attempt on Hamas leader in Jordan Khalid Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
September 25 -- Two Israeli Mossad agents, carrying fake
Canadian passports, attacked Mashaal outside his Amman office and
injected poison into his ear. Mashaal was taken to hospital for
treatment and the two Israelis were detained. Jordanian officials
described the incident as "a quarrel" between Canadian tourists
and Mashaal's driver, but Hamas insisted it was an assassination
attempt launched by Mossad and vowed to attack Israeli targets
worldwide in revenge.
</P>
<P>
September 27 -- Mashaal was treated with an antidote after
Israel opened its poison at the request of Jordan's King Hussein
and reportedly the persuasion of U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
September 28 -- The Israeli Embassy in Amman denied Israeli
agents' involvement in the bungled attempt on Mashaal's life, even
after Jordan admitted that Mashaal was actually attacked. But a
top-level Israeli delegation led by Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, National infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and
security officials visited Amman secretly to negotiate the release
of the two Israeli agents.
</P>
<P>
September 30 -- Jordan's King Hussein publicly called on
Israel to release jailed Hamas founder and spiritual leader
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin who was sentenced to life in 1989.
</P>
<P>
October 1 -- Yassin was released in a secret overnight
operation and flown to a hospital in Amman by a Jordanian
helicopter, apparently under a deal between Israel and Jordan on
prisoner exchange. He was said to have Israeli tacit approval of
his return to his homeland Gaza.
</P>
<P>
October 2 -- Canada announced it was recalling its ambassador
to Israel to protest the use of Canadian passports by Israeli
agents in the botched mission in Amman.
</P>
<P>
October 4 -- Jordan said Israel would soon release dozens more
Palestinian prisoners including senior Hamas leaders.
</P>
<P>
October 5 -- After six hours of negotiations, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon failed to reach a deal with
King Hussein to win the release of two Mossad hit men.
</P>
<P>
October 6 -- Under a secret deal on releasing prisoners, an
Israeli helicopter flew to Jordan in the morning to pick up the
two detained Mossad agents. In the afternoon, Yassin gave a news
conference in Amman before leaving for Gaza, vowing to continue
armed struggle until the end of Israeli occupation. The Hamas
leader was accorded a hero's welcome in the Gaza Stadium attended
by tens of thousands of cheering Palestinian residents and
officials.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Palestinians and nine Jordanians were set free from
Israeli jails after the two Israeli agents returned home. In the
evening Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu held the first
press conference after the incident to defend the attack on
Mashaal but said a "clarification committee" would be appointed to
investigate the government's handling of the Mashaal affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Not to Seek Military Confrontation With US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran said here today that
it does not look for military confrontation with the American
forces in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Ali Shamkhani said "I do not see any
reason for conflict between the Iranian forces and the American
forces. We are not seeking confrontation."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister made the statement at a press
conference held here this morning on a question whether the
Iranian forces and the American forces would have conflict as
USS Nimitz Aircraft Carrier is approaching the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
However, Shamkhani added, "We do not know the intention of the
other side," which he referred to the American forces deployed in
the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the purpose of deploying USS Nimitz Aircraft
Carrier by the United States is to legitimatize its presence in
the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian defense minister said that Iran was interested in
holding joint maneuvers with the Arabian Gulf countries as part of
Iran's policy of strengthening regional peace and security and
beefing up the self-defense capabilities of littoral states.
</P>
<P>
"Iran will positively review any offer for joint maneuvers
with the regional countries," he said, noting that Iran has been
calling for such war games among regional states.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran was keen on forming defensive pacts with the
Arabian Gulf countries and signing a regional non-aggression
pact.
</P>
<P>
"One of our goals and dreams is to achieve the defensive
pact," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States said Friday that it had dispatched the
aircraft carrier battle group to the Persian Gulf in the
wake of Iranian incursions into "no-fly zone" in Southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the USS Nimitz and accompanying warships "is
related to our ability to carry out responsibility given to us by
the international community," White House spokesman Michael
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The move came in response to air raids carried out by Iranian
warplanes earlier this week against opposition targets in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. forces in the region currently include five Tomahawk-
capable destroyers, three frigates and two minesweepers. The
battle group en route to the Persian Gulf comprises the
Nimitz, with about 80 tactical aircraft on board, along with
two cruisers, one destroyer, one frigate, an attack submarine
and support ship.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the White House announced the deployment of
USS Nimitz Aircraft Carrier in the Persian Gulf, Iran has been
highly nervous about the latest move and termed the U.S. naval
fleet a threat to regional security.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Navy Commander Admiral Abbas Mohtaj noted that the
presence of foreign powers mainly the United States in the
Persian Gulf region is unlawful and threatens the security of
the region.
</P>
<P>
"The arrival of tens of U.S. warships in the sensitive region
of the Persian Gulf is regarded as a major cause of tension and
insecurity at this part of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The presence of alien forces is aimed at heightening tension
and selling million dollars worth of arms to the Arab countries
of the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
noted that the growing friendly atmosphere between Iran and the
regional states has made the redeployment of the U.S. warships in
the Persian Gulf seem as an act in desperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the dispatch of the USS Nimitz Aircraft Carrier to the
Persian Gulf is an attempt to misportray the Persian Gulf as
trouble spot.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans are dissatisfied with the growing confidence and
 friendship between Iran and its neighboring Muslim states in the
region and see the current atmosphere as harmful to their
illegitimate interests in the Persian Gulf," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
