<HEADLINE> Japan's Opposition Parties Boycott Budget Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Three Japanese opposition parties
today boycotted the debate at the Budget Committee of the House of
Representatives, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The parties, including the New Frontier Party (NFP), walked out
after their call for testimony by a scandal-tainted oil dealer was
rejected by the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
The budget committee of the lower house of Diet, or parliament,
was forced to run a question-and-answer session without members
from the NFP, the Democratic Party of Japan and the Taiyo Party.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told reporters that
his party may agree to summon oil dealer Junichi Izui to the Diet
for questioning over his alleged payoff to LDP politicians.
</P>
<P>
Izui, now standing trial on bribery, fraud and tax evasion
charges, claims to have donated massive political funds to six
influential politicians of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The three opposition parties had warned that they would not
attend deliberations at the lower house budget committee unless
the subpoena of Izui is promised, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
