<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Reveals Severe Trauma Among Afghan Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The majority of children in
the Afghan capital of Kabul are experiencing serious traumatic
stress during the on-going bloody fighting in the war-torn
country, a UNICEF study said.
</P>
<P>
About 72 percent of the children interviewed experienced the
death of a family member between 1992 and 1996 and in 40 percent
of these cases the child lost a parent, according to the results
of a new study "Psychosocial Assessment of Children Exposed to War
Related Violence in Kabul", issued here today by the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
The study, the first of its kind in Afghanistan, was conducted
by a UNICEF mental health specialist and is based on interviews
with more than 300 children aged between 8 and 18 years in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The results indicate that almost all of the children have been
witnesses to acts of violence during the fighting while two thirds
of them saw dead bodies or parts of bodies and nearly half saw
many people killed at a time in rocket and artillery attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We are reminded daily of the physical scars of war on
children, but the results of this study confront us with the fact
that the mental wounds are as deep," said UNICEF Executive
Director Carol Bellamy.
</P>
<P>
Nearly three-quarters of the children said that they do not
expect to live to adulthood and the majority of them suffer from
nightmares, anxiety and concentration problems which also affect
their appetite and their ability to play, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The war in Afghanistan, now in its 19th year, has affected
almost every family in the country. Kabul has borne the brunt of
the fighting over the past five years, being the center of the
power struggle among various warring factions, most recently
between the ex-government and the Taliban forces which are now in
control.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most significant findings of the study is the
chronic nature of the trauma being experienced," explained Dr.
Leila Gupta, author of the study. "The psychological impact is not
short-lived."
</P>
<P>
"Violence has been a hugely influential factor in the emotional
development of these children and has dramatically affected their
views of themselves and of their future," she said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all the children interviewed said that they worry about
what will happen to them and their families in the future and 90
percent of them said they would die during the conflict, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF has begun to train a core group of 15 mental health
workers in ways to help children express their painful experiences
through artwork, writing, role playing and other activities.
</P>
<P>
"While the UNICEF study focuses on children, it is clear adults
in Kabul have also experienced loss in their families as a result
of the horrific events that they witnessed during the fighting,"
said Gupta.
</P>
<P>
"In order to help the children we must also address the needs
of their families, care givers and communities to help them cope
with these losses and traumas," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safina out as 10 New Parties Registered in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
refused to register the Safina Party but allowed 10 others,
bringing the total number of registered political parties to 21.
</P>
<P>
Safina was denied registration on the grounds of "peace,
welfare and good order in Kenya", local press today quoted
Registrar of Societies Omondi Mbago as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rejection of Safina, which has been lobbying for its
registration since 1995, provoked immediate condemnation from its
officials who termed the decision by Mbago as "wrong,
politically-motivated and sinister."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Islamic Party of Kenya (IPK) leader Sheikh Balala
said IPK was not ready for registration, adding the governmental
move was a blessing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
"If we accept registration by KANU (the ruling Kenya African
National Union), we shall have been soaked in KANU's dirty
waters. It is our prayer the IPK is not registered," he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Treaty Party of Kenya and People's Democratic
Congress were also denied registration.
</P>
<P>
The newly-registered parties are Liberal Party of Kenya,
People's Party of Kenya, Kenya Socialist Party, New People's
Democratic Party, Democratic Assistance Party, the Reform of
Political and Kenya Union, Green African Party and the Umma
Patriotic Party of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The rest are Kenya Nationalist People's Democratic Party and
the Forum for the Restoration of Democracy for the People
(FORD-People), which originally was Kenneth Matiba faction of
FORD-Asili.
</P>
<P>
The registration of the new parties is in line with the
recommendations of the Inter-Party Parliamentary Group (IPPG)
reforms package which also instructed the Registrar to give
reasons whenever an application was denied.
</P>
<P>
All the parties were registered between September 29 and
October 2.
</P>
<P>
If all the parties field presidential candidates, Kenya's
presidential race will attract 21 contenders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
