<HEADLINE> S. Africa, India Sign Trade Promotion Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and India
Monday signed a commercial alliance agreement aimed at
strengthening trade and economic cooperation between the two
countries, Business Day newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, it didn't say where or by whom the agreement was
signed.
</P>
<P>
The India-South Africa Commercial Alliance would be made up of
government officials and representatives from different sectors,
including the private sectors, it said.
</P>
<P>
Jointly chairing the alliance would be South Africa's trade
and industry director-general Zav Rustomjee and the Indian
commerce secretary.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral, who is in South
Africa for a week-long visit, said the joint commission had
"identified a target of 2 billion U.S. Dollars for our bilateral
trade by 2000."
</P>
<P>
Sectoral forums of the alliance would strengthen ties and work
out cooperative programs, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
South African Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said the
alliance, especially the sectoral forums, would facilitate
cooperation at an operational level. The partnership with India
was based on economic, political and historical ties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gujral said the volume of business between the two countries
was constantly rising. In the past year, bilateral trade exceeded
600 million Rand (128 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Gujral arrived in Johannesburg Sunday night and left for Cape
Town Monday for talks with South African President Nelson Mandela
and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Mandela, the two leaders will sign three
agreements in tourism, mining and cooperation in science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
South African-Indian relations saw significant improvement in
recent years. Mandela have visited India for three times after he
took office in 1994. In the last three year, 18 South African
ministers have visited India.
</P>
<P>
A total of 13 agreements have been signed between the two
countries, encompassing political, diplomatic, scientific,
defense and commercial ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
