<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Prices Up in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The price of foodstuff in
Indonesia has increased 1.91 percent in average due to
long-running dry season and monetary turmoil, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
The price hike happens to most of foods, Beddu Amang, chairman
of the State Logistics Agency (Bulog), said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to him, prices of peanuts go up 6.6 percent,
vegetables 5.83 percent, fruits 3.56 percent, processed foods
2.65 percent, fat and cooking oil 2.16 percent, rice and cassava
1.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the prices of meat, eggs, milk and flavors
decrease 0.29 percent, 0.47 percent and 0.51 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The prices of non-foodstuffs also increase like housing,
garment as well as various goods and services, he added, which
respectively go up 0.82 percent, 0.61 percent and 1.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Amang said, the price hike is still at normal level according
to the current long drought situation and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
To maintain stable food price, he said, Bulog conducts market
operations everyday in all regions throughout the country. Bulog
also distributes rice to the peripheral regions including Irian
Jaya and Kalimantan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Though Indonesia's rupiah has fallen 50 percent against the
U.S. dollar since the beginning of this year, the Bulog chairman
said, Bulog does not increase flour price since it still has old
stock in adequate amount.
</P>
<P>
Rice stock in the country amounts to 2.8 million tons, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, long-running dry season causes food shortage in
several regions and claimed 413 lives in Irian Jaya. Government
officials said that the victims died from starvation, dehydration,
respiratory problems and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
The drought also contributes to forest fires in Kalimantan and
Sumatra that spread haze to neighboring countries -- Malaysia,
Singapore, the Philippines and Thailand.  
</P>
