<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Top Business Groups Poor in Management Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Twenty of 30 largest South Korean
business conglomerates showed a failing mark in management
performance this year.
</P>
<P>
The LG Economic Research Institute reported that only 10 of the
30 top groups showed their return on invested capital (ROIC) over
the market interest rate.
</P>
<P>
Now bankrupt or near-bankrupt, Hanbo, Jinro, Sammi, Dainong and
Kia groups registered 1.7 percent, 1.9 percent, 3.2 percent, 5.5
percent and 8.7 percent in ROIC last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures, said the LG institute's report on corporate
business performance, went below the market rate of 12 percent
last year, and much lower than the five groups' average ROIC over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Top five conglomerates on average showed profitability of 23.3
percent for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The Samsung Group placed first with 35.3 percent, followed by
LG with 31.9 percent, Sunkyong with 25.3 percent, Hyundai with
24.0 percent and Daewoo with 15.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, however, Sunkyong was on top with 43.7 percent,
Samsung in second with 26.1 percent and Hyundai in third with 23.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Return on invested capital is a typical profitability index of
evaluating management performance, which measures the proportion
of earnings to assets used for operation for a business year.
</P>
<P>
The percentages below the market rate indicate that it would be
less lucrative to do business than to buy bonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
