<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-PM Urges Thais Not to Give Up to Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai statesman and former prime
minister Prem Tinsulanonda urged Thai people to exercise tolerance
and not to surrender to the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a rare interview with senior editors of a few local
newspapers Monday, Prem said, "The country is sick and needs
treatment. There must be confidence in the sick nation and in
doctors providing the treatment."
</P>
<P>
He added that confidence is of utmost importance before
anything can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Prem called on the people to show confidence in the efforts
made by the three key persons in charge of the country's financial
matters, Deputy Prime Minister Virabongsa Ramangura, Finance
Minister Thanong Bidaya and Bank of Thailand Governor Chaiyawat
Wibulswasdi.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't have trust in them, we cannot move forward," said
the well-respected statesman who had been a non-elected prime
minister for eight years until 1988.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure, Thailand experienced a major economic slump
and the baht was devalued in 1984. But Prem's administration has
often been cited as one of the most politically-stable, and one
which helped lay the foundation for the country's strong economic
growth in the subsequent 10 years after 1987.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister also urged business people to be
considerate of their workers by trying to avoid lay-offs.
</P>
<P>
"Poor people cannot do anything. Goods are dearer and earnings
are lower. Their children must go to school. They cannot maneuver
and have no way out. They can only remain under the reduced value
of money," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Thai people "to accept the situation and fight
with tolerance... We cannot escape nor run away from the problems.
We must fight on together." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
