<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Suspected Bosnian War Criminals Flown to the Hague </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ten Bosnian Croats suspected of
committing crimes in the Bosnian civil war were flown today to an
international tribunal in the Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The surrender of the war criminal suspects was the result of
recent negotiations among U.S. envoy Robert Gelbard, Croatian
President Fanjo Tudjman and Bosnian Croat leader Kresimir Zubak.
</P>
<P>
Ivic Pasalic, an advisor to Tudjman, said the Croatian
government helped arrange the surrender in order to fulfill its
commitments to the war tribunal under the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
It was also aimed at maintaining the overall interest of
Croatia and Bosnian Croats, he said, urging that the United States
and the international community keep their promises to his people.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said Croatia made the move under tremendous
pressure from the United States, but obtained the U.S. guarantee
that the 10 suspects would be tried "fairly" within 3-5 months.
</P>
<P>
In his comment, Gelbard said the move signaled "an important
and positive step" in the peace process initiated by the Dayton
accord that ended a war of three years and a half in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
With the latest development, the U.S. government is now
expected to consider supporting Croatia's bid for loans from
international financial institutions such as the World Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
