<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cracks Found in Jamuna Bridge in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Numerous cracks have developed in
the piers and deck slabs of the 900 million U.S. dollar Jamuna
Multipurpose Bridge (JMB), which may ultimately lead to the
collapse of the most prestigious project in Bangladesh, a local
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
Local daily The New Nation said the JMB authority is expected
to hold a three-day meeting today to discuss this serious problem
which might jeopardize the future of the 4.8 kilometer-long, 18.5
meter-wide bridge.
</P>
<P>
With the participation of foreign experts and the donors, the
meeting is to find remedial measures for the cracks of the bridge,
which is expected to function through centuries after completion.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the JMB is divided into four sections and
the work was awarded to three contractors including two foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that the cracks were found at almost
every segment of the completed works -- deck slabs, hinge
segments, pier stems and pile cap shells.
</P>
<P>
The cracks may have developed because of lack of control of
moisture content, improper transverse stressing or some other
reasons, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
They added that the contractors should be inquired whether they
had followed the design truthfully and used the material according
to the specification.
</P>
<P>
The JMB project, funded by the Bangladeshi government and its
donors, is scheduled to complete its two-year construction by the
end of this year, which may not be possible now, the sources
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
