<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fight Against Marine Pollution Urged in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- It is called in Zanzibar
of Tanzania to develop integrated regional management strategies
to combat marine pollution in the western coasts of the Indian
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Zanzibar Minister for Agriculture,
Livestock Development and Natural Resources Adam Mwakanjuki while
opening a four-day workshop in Zanzibar Monday on the
implementation of the global program of action for the protection
of the marine environment from land-based activities in the east
African region.
</P>
<P>
According to a news dispatch reaching here today, Mwakanjuki
said that in small island states like Zanzibar which have few
resources, the marine environment is the principal sources of
economic sustenance.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in most countries of the region, emphasis has
understandably been on economic exploitation of marine resources
and very little regard to environmental conservation.
</P>
<P>
He observed that marine and coastal environments are extremely
fragile and sensitive and that there is a limit to the ocean's
carrying capacity.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there is therefore a need to consider the amount
of waste which can be dumped into the ocean without causing
damages.
</P>
<P>
Mwakanjuki pointed out that poorly managed agricultural
activities, dumping of untreated domestic and industrial wastes
along coastal areas have all contributed to the degradation of
numerous marine resources.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "The threat to the productive capacity and
biodiversity of marine environment is so real -- and so in the
danger to human health." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Halts Lessening Foreign Investments' Ratio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
(PSE) is holding in abeyance its plan to change the foreign
investments' ratio in the local bourses, the Philippine News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vet Vitug, chief of the PSE corporate communications
department, said the plan was shelved for a while in light of the
implications brought about by the region-wide currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said he had no idea of whether it could still be revived
while the currency turmoil still prevails and has pulled down the
peso and the local bourses to unreasonable levels.
</P>
<P>
PSE president Jose Luis Yulo put forward earlier this year the
plan that seeks to keep foreign investors' interest in the local
stocks at 40 percent instead of the current more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
This way, the shares controlled by foreign investors at the
stock exchange will not be influenced so much whenever these
investors pull out of their money to other booming markets, Yulo
said.
</P>
<P>
At this time, a slight rumor in the business community would
immediately tip the scale of stock market investments in the
country, thus affecting the economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Due to the currency turbulence, the 30-share composite index of
the Philippine Stock Exchange has fallen more than 800 points,
closing at 1920.63 points at today's trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers' Strike Talks Deadlock in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The talks on teachers' pay
dispute between the Kenyan government and the Kenya National
Union of Teachers (KNUT) has reached a deadlock, the Daily Nation
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the teachers' union vowed to continue with
the four-day-long strike until the Kenyan government meets its
demands.
</P>
<P>
The government issued a statement last night, advising all
teachers who started a nationwide strike on October 1 to report
to their duty stations by 8 a.m. tomorrow or face unspecified
punishment.
</P>
<P>
The statement signed by Kenyan Education Minister Joseph
Kamotho was issued when the talks aimed at ending the strike was
going on under the chairmanship of Labour Minister Philip
Masinde.
</P>
<P>
After learning this development, John Katumanga, Chairman of
the Teachers Service Commission said that "it is unfair, immoral
and against all known labour laws to make prejudicial statements
when the talks were going on."
</P>
<P>
The striking teachers are demanding a salary increase ranging
between 150 and 200 percent, but the government has agreed to
give a 10 to 28 percent salary increment.
</P>
<P>
The KNUT Secretary General Ambrose Adongo noted that "we went
to the talks with an open mind" and prepared a proposal of
spreading the salary increase over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed, the Kenyan government has not offered
anything new to the teachers at the talks and kept on saying
there is no money.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said that the talks had to be adjourned to
facilitate "further consultations at the political level" and to
"give the parties time to see whether all grounds were acceptable
to them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
