<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Parliament Will Endorse Law to Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian president Negasso
Gidada said Monday that Ethiopian parliament is expected to
endorse a law which will help streamline the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Addressing to houses of federation and people's
representatives which began their third year tenure on Monday,
the president told the two houses that it is beyond doubt that
the private sector has an irreplaceable role to play. However, he
said the sector does not have the capacity to play a decisive
role at the moment.
</P>
<P>
He said, as market economy is new to the country, the quality
and quantity of the products of the private sector is minimal,
adding that a close cooperation between the private sector and
government is not yet in place.
</P>
<P>
The house of people's representatives is expected to ratify a
proclamation providing for the reorganization of the private
sector in a much better shape, he said, and added that a law
relevant to small scale and micro-enterprises would also be
issued this year.
</P>
<P>
On revising the investment code, the president said to attract
more investment, the incumbent investment code must be revised
and the house of people's representatives would also ratify the
ammended law this year.
</P>
<P>
The president referred to the problems arising from rain
failure this year. He said rain failure has fully destroyed crops
in some areas and significantly reduced harvest in other areas.
</P>
<P>
There has been shortage of potable water while the amount of
water in some of the dams has diminished causing a reduction in
the supply of electric power, he continued.
</P>
<P>
He said, the government believes in the need for foreign
assistance which should be complemented with local initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
