<HEADLINE> Private Economy in Hubei Developing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate for the private
economy in central China's Hubei province has doubled the national
average over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The province is home to 32.500 private enterprises with
registered capital of 32.9 billion yuan (3.96 billion US dollars),
respective 16-fold and 19-fold increases on 1992.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of private enterprises has accounted for 42.5
percent of the province's total retail sales volume, up 32.5
percentage points from 1992.
</P>
<P>
Private firms have established more than 100 limited liability
companies, many of which have gained listings on domestic stock
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that the 60 percent of employees in
Hubei's private enterprises have earned college degrees at least
and the private enterprises pay to the state a total of 1.5
billion yuan in taxes each year over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
A large amount of private investment have shifted from the
commercial and catering sectors to industrial manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Over 670 private enterprises have invested a total of over two
billion yuan in agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry and
aquatic products sectors over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Thirty seven public-owned enterprises in Wuhan, the provincial
capital, have either merged with or been purchased by profitable
private firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
