<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helsinki Holds Energy-Saving Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- An energy-saving week started
here today as winter sets in this Scandinavian country.
</P>
<P>
Finland has scant energy resources that can provide only 30
percent of the energy needed by the country. Since the oil crisis
in the 1970s, the government has adopted a series of policies,
trying to encourage people to explore every means possible to save
energy.
</P>
<P>
Timer-controlled lamps are used everywhere, in dwellers'
buildings or in public facilities. Central heating is now common,
in-house heating devices are smaller, and thermostats are widely
used that can be set to keep room temperatures stable.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200 drivers of the city bus service have taken lessons
on how to save fuel, according to a staff member of the bus
service.
</P>
<P>
An energy-saving exhibition held concurrently with the
energy-saving week reminds people of the need to cultivate good
habits of turning off light upon leaving a place, and the need for
rational use of air-conditioners in public places.
</P>
<P>
computer users were advised to save energy at night and over
the weekend and people were told to replace old, energy-consuming
refrigerators at home.
</P>
<P>
A nation-wide campaign for energy saving will be underway. The
Trade and Industry Ministry will stage an energy-saving day
Thursday that will lay emphasis on techniques for less energy
consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
