<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-U.S. Trade Dispute Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indo-U.S. trade dispute
continues and the United States has turned on the heat towards
India's trade curbs.
</P>
<P>
The United States has put on the agenda for the World Trade
Organization (WTO) October 16 meeting a request to set up a panel
to probe India's so-called quantitative restrictions (QRS) regime,
a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The American request came late on Friday (October 3) evening.
Indian officials had earlier said that October 6 was the deadline
for closing the agenda for the October 16 WTO meeting, but the
actual deadline should be October 3. The United States
deliberately put forward its request until the last day to make it
impossible for India to make a revised offer.
</P>
<P>
In its request, the United States has used the same words it
used two months ago when it complained to the WTO that India
continues to use a precarious balance of payments (BOP) situation
as an excuse to restrict imports when its BOP is no longer
threatened. As reported earlier, India's foreign reserves of 30
billion U.S. dollars make its BOP argument very weak.
</P>
<P>
The United States has indicated that the consultations with
India have not resulted in a mutually agreeable solution. It has
therefore sought the constitution of a panel whose ruling would be
legally binding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
