<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, India Discuss Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The cooperation between Russia
and India in military technology will not pose a threat to the
security and stability of the Asia-Pacific region, Russian Defense
Minister Ignor Dmitriyevich Sergeyev said here today.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev made the statement to the press after meeting with his
Indian counterpart Mulayam Singh Yadav, who arrived in Moscow
Monday on a five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation will not disturb the balance of forces in the
region, Sergeyev said, adding that Instead, it will help stabilize
the balance.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the cooperation is being conducted under
the year 2000 Military Technological Cooperation Plan between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also reached an agreement on the extension of the
plan's duration, the Russian minister told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Mulayam said the relations between India and Russia are of
great significance to world peace.
</P>
<P>
The two defense ministers discussed solutions to the activities
of extremists in Central and Western Asia, including countries
neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
The two sides shared the view on this issue, Mulayam said.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said that the Indian military delegation will also
negotiate the possibility of purchasing two submarines (about
800 million U.S. dollars each) and some other military equipment
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
India is a traditional importer of Russian weapons. From 1990
to 1996, It bought 3.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of weapons from
Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
