<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Holds Conference on Global Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank opened today a
six-day conference on environment, during which Indonesia's forest
fires, the tempestuous effect of El Nino and the need for tougher
curbs on greenhouse gas emissions are major topics.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred of the world's scientists, government
ministers, economists, lawyers and environmentalists attended the
bank's Conference on Environmentally and Socially Sustainable
Development.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address to the conference, World Bank Group
President, James D. Wolfensohn, warned that unless the world moves
aggressively to safeguard its environment, and merges social,
environmental, and economic concerns together in charting a
sustainable global future, the lives of its children would suffer.
</P>
<P>
The conference will hold a series of related meetings on the
current state-of-health of the global environment, covering the
increasing evidence of climate change, the steady destruction of
the world's coral reefs, and the threat posed to forests and
farmland by poor environmental practices.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has noticed that despite the fact that many
countries have signed environmental treaties such as the U.N.
Framework Convention on Climate Change and other agreements
governing seas and oceans, forests and hazardous waste, few
signatories have so far carried out their legal obligations.
</P>
<P>
A lack of shared interests between international scientists,
economists, and lawyers may be a key reason for this slow progress.
</P>
<P>
By convening the conference, the bank hopes to settle some
issues that prevent countries from living up to their existing
legal obligations and clear the way for new environmental
treaties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
