<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Raging Fires in Indonesia Cause Heavy Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian government officials
estimated forest fires and haze in the country have caused heavy
losses.
</P>
<P>
Forestry Minister Djamaludin Suryohadikusumo disclosed Monday
that fires have razed at least 96,700 hectares of forests chalking
up an estimated 12.3 million U.S. dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the forests lost, 70,200 hectares were
productive forests while the rest was protected and preserved
forests.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Transportation Minister Haryanto Dhanutirto said the
smoke caused by the fires, better known as the haze, has cost the
nation's airlines up to 5.4 million U.S. dollars in losses since
January.
</P>
<P>
"A total of 3,372 flights have been canceled during that period
with total opportunity loss damages reaching up to 5.4 million
U.S. dollars," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the smoke haze has also adversely affected land and sea
transportation, particularly in Sumatra, Kalimantan and Irian Jaya
islands, but he did not quantify the damages.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Sjarifuddin Baharsjah also said the
slash-and-burn methods for land clearing have affected a total
land area of 121,630 hectares in the country.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, plantation companies that are suspected of having
employed slash and burn methods to clear land have been given 15
days to deny causing any fires, which are the source of the smoke
haze that has blanketed parts of Indonesia and several other
nations in Southeast Asia, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Fires have occurred on 242 plantation companies' estates, he
said, adding that 29 of them were suspected of having burned to
clear land.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said earlier, thick smoke from fires
raging across 300,000 hectares of forest had been hanging over
Malaysia and Singapore during the past two months. At one stage it
also reached the Philippines and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 30,000 people in Sumatra and Kalimantan, plus
tens of thousands in Malaysia and Singapore, have reportedly been
suffering from respiratory illnesses and eye irritations.
</P>
</TEXT>
