<HEADLINE> Prompt Action Against Cholera Epidemic in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's public health
authorities have taken prompt action to prevent the spreading of
cholera following the discovery of over 100 positive cases in a
fishing village at the north western coastal area of Chilaw
lately.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic began spreading about a week ago in the area,
which lies some 70 kilometers north of Colombo. It is believed
that the virus causing the disease has come from India after some
people returned from their pilgrim trip to the neighboring
country.
</P>
<P>
Medical department sources said today that medical teams have
been sent to Chilaw to carry out a massive public health campaign
there. They are helping people chlorinate wells, burn rubbish and
clean hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Ice cream has been prohibited from selling in the area. In
hospitals, special wards have been set up to accommodate suspect
patients.
</P>
<P>
The area has a population of around 25,000 whose sanitary
conditions sometimes leave much to be desired, sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
