<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Latin America (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil ranked first in the number of
companies obtaining certification from the International
Organization for Standardization (ISO-900), Brazil's Association
of Technical Standards said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,144 Brazilian companies had been certificated by
August by the organization whose norms are designed to guarantee
the quality of services and products.
</P>
<P>
There are 361 Argentine companies and 25 Uruguayan companies
that have got certification.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's Timber exports dropped by 35 percent to
65,000 cubic meters this year from 100,000 cubic meters in 1994
due to new legislation protecting some tree species.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Brazil sold abroad 611 million dollars worth of raw
timber and wood products.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the second biggest tropical timber producer in the
world after Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA -- The European Union (EU) will raise its funds for
the Fishery Development Central American Program to 3.2 million
dollars next year, the EU representative office in Tegucigalpa
said.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to encourage a better use of sea resources in
the isthmuses in the Atlantic and the Pacific, and help implement
a common fishery policy among Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica will suspend its shrimp fishing in the
Nicoya Gulf from October 30 to November 30 this year to protect
its reproduction, the Institute of Fishery said.
</P>
<P>
This follows a seasonal close in June and July this year.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Trade Ministry said shrimp exports reached 45
million dollars from January to August, a 36 percent increase over
the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's domestic truck sales totaled 739 units in
August, up 3.2 percent over the same month in 1996, the National
Automobile Association said.
</P>
<P>
This drove the truck sales in the first eight months up to
6,402 units, the association said. It estimated a total domestic
sale of 10,000 vehicles in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mercedez Benz headed the sales with 862 units or 13.5 percent
of the market share, followed by Ford with 828 units sold and
Isuzu with 588 units.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Coffee production in Nicaragua shrank in the 1996-97
season and will hurt the country's exports this year, Nicaragua's
Coffee Producers Union said.
</P>
<P>
The organization's president, Amilcar Navarro, said coffee
growers are facing a string of problems, including plant illness,
lack of credits, poor transportation facilities and robbery of
coffee during transport.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil has banned the import of ostriches and
ornamental birds from the United States after a recent shipment of
ostriches carrying a dangerous virus that affects birds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
