<HEADLINE> Government's Budget Proposals Inadequate: Bertinotti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The government's proposals to
Communist Refoundation leaders in an attempt to win their support
for the 1998 draft budget and avoid a government crisis are
inadequate, party secretary Fausto Bertinotti said today.
</P>
<P>
He said the budget contained too many welfare cuts and not
enough measures to boost employment.
</P>
<P>
His party asked the government to "give a sign of equity" by
withdrawing its plan to cut big welfare spending from the draft
budget and by reducing or eliminating costs for certain types of
medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Pensions and health care spending are among the key areas
targeted in the 5 trillion lire (2.8 billion U.S. dollars) in
welfare spending cuts called for in the budget.
</P>
<P>
This hard left party also demanded the government shorten the
working week from 40 to 35 hours and to create jobs in the south
where the unemployment rate is the highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Without the support of the communist deputies in the lower
house, the Chamber of Deputies, Prime Minister Romano Prodi has
next to no chance of passing the budget, which is seen as vital to
Italy's hopes of joining the launch of a European single currency
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
It may also trigger a vote of confidence. If Prodi fails in the
vote, he has to tender his resignation and bring down his 17-month
center-left government.
</P>
<P>
Bertinotti's party commands less than 10 percent of the vote
but its 34 deputies hold the balance of power in the lower house
of parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
