<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Step in Modernizing Air Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine has decided that Boeing and
Airbus Industries will serve as its long-term suppliers to
modernize the state-run carrier Air Ukraine fleet.
</P>
<P>
Air Ukraine is planning to buy two long-range Boeing 76-200ER
and three medium-range Airbus 320-200 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The selection of two companies, announced as winners of a
tender in early May to supply aircraft to Air Ukraine, surprised
those who expected only one supplier to be chosen.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts hailed the decision, but some of them said it
showed Ukraine's dependence on the world's major aviation
superpowers.
</P>
<P>
"By this decision, Ukrainian leaders killed two birds with one
stone," said Alexy Golub, an aviation industry analyst with Den
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
First, it is good because the current condition of Ukraine's
flagship carriers could cause much harm to the nation's future
image, said Golub.
</P>
<P>
Second, Golub said, refusal to buy either Boeing or Airbus
would automatically bury the number of joint projects that are
currently under way between Ukraine and other international
aircraft companies.
</P>
<P>
Defending the forthcoming purchase, Air Ukriane officials
contend the new planes will be more efficient and will consume
less fuel than the present fleet made by the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine's aircraft fleet is already very old. It's almost
impossible to penetrate the international market with our outdated
Tu-134s and Il-62s," Vatily Gusin, an Air Ukraine official, said.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the shortage of spare parts supplied by enterprises in
other CIS countries, Air Ukraine, with 12,000 employees, has
grounded about 40 percent of its 250 aircraft, most of which are
Illiushin-62s and Tupolev-134s produced in the days of the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Since Ukraine, which failed to inherit any of the Il-80s, a
huge 350-seat jumbo jet made in the former Soviet Union, is still
using Il-62s on international routes, which, Golub complained, are
very inefficient economically due to high fuel consumption.
</P>
<P>
"One Il-62 consumes 150 percent more fuel than a similar-sized
Boeing, which makes our current trans-Atlantic routes
unprofitable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We can hardly attract passengers with the Il-62 aircraft. That
is why we need the new planes," he added
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Il-62s do not meet safety standards of many
countries, including the United States, and face future
prohibitions on landing rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
