<HEADLINE> Canada Gets No Assurances From Israel on Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government said
today it has got no assurances that Israel will not use Canadian
passports for covert operations in the future.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Israel has given any assurances that it will not
use Canadian passports again, Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd
Axworthy replied: "Not at this stage, no."
</P>
<P>
Khaled Meshal, political chief of the militant Islamic group
Hamas, was assaulted outside his office in Amman, Jordan, on
September 25.
</P>
<P>
The two attackers, carrying Canadian passports, were arrested
and proven to be agents of Israel's secret service Mossad.
</P>
<P>
The two agents returned to Israel this afternoon, in exchange
for the release of a Hamas leader, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Axworthy spoke with Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy on the phone about the passport incident.
</P>
<P>
During the conversation, Levy expressed to Axworthy his "very
deep regret" at the use of Canadian passports by two Israeli
agents in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Levy promised his Canadian counterpart that Israel will
investigate into the assassination attempt and that Canada will
receive a report on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Canada recalled its ambassador to Israel to protest
the use of forged Canadian passports by the two agents.
</P>
<P>
The latest passport incident apparently broke a tacit agreement
between Canada and Israel that the latter would bar its secret
service from using Canadian passports after they were caught doing
so in 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
