<HEADLINE> Italy: No Interference Intended in Algeria's Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Italy's expressed readiness to
contribute to finding a solution to the crisis in Algeria, even by
acting as a mediator between the opposing sides, should have been
seen as a gesture of friendship and not an attempt to interfere in
Algeria's internal affairs, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Dini's remarks came in response to a call Sunday by the
Algerian Foreign Ministry to Italy's ambassador, who was asked to
explain comments Dini made Saturday in Palermo, when he said: "We
cannot just sit and watch the tragedy in Algeria, we have a moral
responsibility to do something.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that our proposal was not directed at the
government but at those responsible for the massacres," said Dini.
</P>
<P>
"Italy knows that this is the way it is, that the Algerians
think they can resolve the problem by themselves. But after the
recent massacres, we thought that it might be possible to bring
together those forces which have abandoned or who claim they are
against the use of violence."
</P>
<P>
Dini stressed any further initiatives will only be possible
"when Algeria shows its readiness." 
</P>
