<HEADLINE> Indonesian Central Bank Intervenes as Rupiah Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rupiah plunged to
another new low Monday dropping to 3,850 against the U.S. dollar
at midday before easing in the afternoon due to Bank Indonesia's
intervention, currency dealers said today.
</P>
<P>
The dealers said the central bank intervened in the spot market
with some 200 million U.S. dollars, which helped prop up the
rupiah to close at 3,710/25 against the opening of 3,725/35.
</P>
<P>
The worsening currency market also perforated trading
activities on the Jakarta Stock Exchange with the main price gauge
falling by 2.58 points to close at 512.89.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers attributed the persistent weakening of the
rupiah to the high demand for dollar from local companies to
refinance their dollar-denominated debt as well as the weak
regional currency markets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said Monday that
the government will not set artificial targets for the rupiah but
will intervene in extraordinary circumstances to save it from
falling further.
</P>
<P>
Despite the ongoing currency crisis, he said, the government
would maintain its free foreign exchange regime.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has plunged 35 percent against the dollar since
early July, with most of the tumble occurring after the government
floated the currency in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Meordiono, who met with President Soeharto Monday, also said
the president called for cooperation between the government, the
private sector and banks to deal with the country's monetary
crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
