<HEADLINE> Drought-Related Deaths Rise in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Another 151 drought-related
deaths have been reported in Indonesia's easternmost province of
Irian Jaya, lifting the toll to at least 413.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures were provided by officials of Jayawijaya
District of Irian Jaya on Monday, saying that large-scale relief
was urgently needed to prevent more casualties.
</P>
<P>
Thousands in remote villages in Irian Jaya scattered throughout
the Jayawijaya, Merauke and Puncak Jaya districts had been
suffering from malnutrition and illnesses over the last three
months, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
They said the rising death toll was because the disaster-hit
villages being so remote. Communication in such areas remained
difficult and the thick haze hindered the delivery of food and
medical relief.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought, which began three months ago, has also
triggered forest fires in the province. The fires have razed
130,135 hectares of forest, local government officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
