<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Percent Volatility Band Set for Philippine Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bankers Association of the
Philippines has decided to impose a two-percent volatility band on
the peso-U.S. dollar trading starting today.
</P>
<P>
Deogracias Vistan, president of the association, said the move
would foil speculative attacks on the peso amid the Southeast
Asian currency turmoil which had pulled the peso to unreasonable
levels.
</P>
<P>
If the peso fluctuates over two percent beyond the reference
rate, trading will be suspended for 30 minutes, Vistan said,
adding if the peso continues to fluctuate even after the
suspension, the band would be narrowed down to one percent upon
resumption of trading.
</P>
<P>
If after three suspensions, the peso still fluctuates beyond
one percent, the association will suspend trading for the day, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"So the rate will not move more than four percent in a day,
either up or down," Vistan said.
</P>
<P>
He said the volatility band would not hamper trading but only
temper wild fluctuations caused in moments of panic.
</P>
<P>
The peso has been battered and devaluated by 31 percent in the
regional currency woes, falling to a new low of 34.926 pesos to
one dollar on Monday's trading.
</P>
<P>
The Bankers Association, which earlier had a volatility band of
1.5 percent, was forced to abandon it on July 11 after the sharp
fall of the peso and other currencies in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
