<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Latin America (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Retail prices showed no variation here in
September, according to Argentina's National Institute of
Statistics and Census.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate has increased 0.5 percent in 1997 and 0.6
percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Prices in the construction sector rose 0.2 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Circulation of pirated software in Uruguay has
fallen to 80 percent of the total software sales from 90 percent
in 1994, Brokerage Price Waterhouse said.
</P>
<P>
But the occurrence of pirated software trafficking in Uruguay
is still the highest in the region, it said in a report to U.S.
Business Software Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The agency attributed the reduction of illegal software to a
wide-ranging control campaign in the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Latin America will have 20 million cellular phone
users by 2000, quadruple the current number, telecom experts here
said.
</P>
<P>
Five million cellular phones were in use in the region in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Cellular phone users will rise to 1.4 billion worldwide by 2010
from the present 100 million, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's production of grains, leguminosae and
oleaginous will top 77.46 million tons this year, 5.7 percent up
from last year, Brazil's Institute of Geography and Statistics
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the country registered production of 73.27 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Japan's automaker Honda opened an automobile
assembly plant in Sao Paulo, its first such plant in Brazil, with
an investment of 800 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The plant will produce 15,000 vehicles in 1998 and is expected
to double the figure the next year. It aims at producing 100,000
units by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Honda opened a motorcycle factory in 1976 in Manaus, capital of
Amazonas state.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's automobile sector exported 2.4
billion dollars worth of vehicles during the first eight months of
this year, up 20 percent from the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Automobile imports rose 90 percent in the January-July period
against the same period in 1996, topping 1.5 billion dollars, the
National Association of Automotive Manufacturers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
