<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico, France Reiterate Stance Against Helms-Burton Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo and his French counterpart, Jacques Chirac, today
reiterated their stance against the United States' Helms-Burton
Law.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also witnessed the signing of accords on the
prevention of drug trafficking and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton Law was enacted in March 1996. The law was
passed to retaliate against Cuba for allegedly shooting down two
U.S. civilian planes in late February that year.
</P>
<P>
The key parts of the law include the prevention of third
countries from selling goods produced in Cuba on U.S. soil;
allowing U.S. citizens and companies to sue anyone using their
property which was seized in Cuba's 1959 revolution; preventing
executives of foreign companies doing business with confiscated
property, and preventing their families from entering the U.S.;
and to impede Cuba's attempts to join international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo has been visiting France since October 4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
