<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Registers Record Current Account Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's current account
deficit reached a record of 6 billion dollars (3.84 billion U.S.
dollars) by the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
This came as a result of the 2.2 billion-dollar (1.4 billion
U.S. dollars) deficit recorded in the second quarter this year,
including 563 million dollars (360 million U.S. dollars) spent on
the purchase of the Australian-built frigate "Te Kaha", said
Statistics New Zealand in a press release received today.
</P>
<P>
The current account, also called the balance of payments,
measures a country's total income and spending. A deficit means
New Zealand is sending more money overseas than it is bringing in.
</P>
<P>
As a percentage of GDP, the current account deficit for the
year ending June 1997 was 6.4 percent, compared with 4.8 percent
for the March 1997 year and 3.7 percent for the June 1996 year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics NZ blamed falls in all of the invisible components -
 services, investment income and transfers- for the rise in the
deficit.
</P>
<P>
The services balance declined due to lower growth in the number
of inbound tourists and their spending. Net investment income has
continued to fall with mixed returns on overseas investments.
Lower inflows of migrants and their funds contributed to a lower
transfers balance, according to Statistics NZ.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
