<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Australia would refuse to sign an international global
warming treaty at the Kyoto climate change summit on December 1 if
it cost jobs and put a "speed limit" on economic growth, Prime
Minister John Howard said for the first time last night.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government is targeting the growing number of
workers who earn hardly more than their social security
entitlements in its tax reform proposals, possibly with a novel
"negative" income tax, or tax cuts, in a bid to address the
concern that many working families have little incentive to work.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Personal details on more than 1200 people, including
politicians, feminists, gay activists, students and ethnic
community leaders, in the state of Victoria were contained in a
secret electronic database kept by a covert arm of the Victoria
police, activities which those targeted deemed "abuse of power"
and "unlawful".
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The strategic failure of Australian management teams has
become a blood bath with the total cost of getting the 1990s
investment drive wrong in the past year has risen to more than 3.7
billion U.S. dollars, the biggest flood of red ink in Australian
corporate history that shareholders have borne.  
</P>
