<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, October 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- New York stocks set more record highs Monday as oil
prices retreated from Friday's jump, and interest rates hit their
lowest level in 19 months in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 61.64 point to 8,100.22,
bringing this year's gain back above 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Space shuttle Atlantis returned to Earth Monday,
bringing home American astronaut Michael Foale after a tumultuous
four and a half months aboard Russia's Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis swooped through a hazy sky and landed at Kennedy Space
Center shortly before 6 p.m. EDT (2200 GMT).
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States is sending
experts to France, Russia and Malaysia as part of a U.S. probe to
determine if sanctions should be imposed in connection with their
companies' 2 billion US dollars natural gas deal with Iran, the
State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- After nearly seven months' deadlock, the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process will be formally resumed
Tuesday, Israeli and Palestinian officials announced here Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
Following a two-hour meeting between Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) deputy head
Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) here in the Laromme Hotel which was
attended by United States special peace envoy Dennis Ross, the
two sides announced to revive the negotiations of the nine joint
committees created to discuss the implementation of the Interim
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- A meeting between Greek and Turkish leaders on the
island of Crete in early November might help improve the relations
between the two countries, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem are expected to hold talks with Greek leadership while
attending the forthcoming Balkan summit on the southern Greek
island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Chiefs of Staff from the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) countries gathered in Doha, Qatar Monday to attend an annual
meeting on strengthening regional security.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the 15th since the GCC was set up 17 years ago,
took place with a joint GCC naval exercises off the coast of
Bahrain which began Saturday and will last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, dubbed "Solidarity-5", came after Iran bombed
two Iranian rebel bases inside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday used his
line-item veto power to strike out 38 projects worth 287 million
U.S. dollars from a military construction bill.
</P>
<P>
"Government must continue to live within its means," Clinton
said in cutting the military outlays from the 9.2 billion U.S.
dollar bill.
</P>
<P>
The vetoed projects include a 19.9 million dollar plan to build
a new wharf for ship repair at Norfolk Naval Shipyard in Virginia;
a 17.9 million dollar pier improvement project at Florida's
Mayport Naval Station; a 16 million dollar railroad project at
Fort Carson, Colo.; four projects in California and three in
Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
