<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Atlantis Returns to Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Space shuttle Atlantis
returned to Earth today, bringing home American astronaut Michael
Foale after a tumultuous four and a half months aboard Russia's
Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis swooped through a hazy sky and landed at Kennedy Space
Center shortly before 6 p.m. EDT (2200 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Thick clouds had prevented Atlantis from landing on Sunday. The
U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) closedly
watched the clouds and wind throughout the afternoon before
finally ordering the seven-member crew the go-ahead to land.
</P>
<P>
As soon as Atlantis rolled to a safe stop, Rhonda Foale, wife
of Michael Foale, gathered near the runway with her two children
and about 400 other well-wishers. She waited cheerfully to welcome
her husband, who has left her to the space for 145 days.
</P>
<P>
Foale, a 40-year-old British-born astrophysicist, moved from
the battered Mir into Atlantis on September 28, one day after the
shuttle arrived with his replacement, a new computer, patches for
holes punched in the hull by a colliding cargo ship, and other
urgently needed supplies.
</P>
<P>
Foale was replaced by American astronaut-physician David Wolf,
to stay in Mir for another four months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Stock Prices Higher, Bond Interest Rates Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks set more record
highs Monday as oil prices retreated from Friday's jump, and
interest rates hit their lowest level in 19 months in the bond
market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 61.64 point to 8,100.22,
bringing this year's gain back above 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other popular stock indexes moved further into record territory
as bonds extended a nearly month-long rally.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list closed at a new high for the
third straight session after a two-month drought. And the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies set a record for the sixth
straight session and 23rd time in 28 sessions.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices rose Monday, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond fell as low as 6.24 percent before settling at 6.26 percent,
its lowest finish since the 6.16 percent of February 16, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by nearly a 5-to-3 margin on
the NYSE, where volume totaled 494.82 million shares, down sharply
from Friday's hefty tally of 619.42 million.
</P>
<P>
The S&AMP;P 500 rose 7.66 to 972.69, pushing this year's gain above
31 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 4.01 to 509.70 for its fourth
straight record close, and the Nasdaq composite index rose 6.04 to
1,721.91 for its third in a row.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 rose 2.18 to 461.70, and the small-company
dominated American Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.88 to
716.80 for its sixth consecutive record close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
