<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Deepened Partnership to Improve Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today called on all member states and all people to
deepen the partnerships to improve the quality of life in all the
world's cities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of World Habitat Day, October 6, 1997,
the U.N. chief said that human beings continued to face a
compelling challenge: how to make cities fit places to live, work
and dream.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said that nearly one half the world's
population now lives in urban areas and two-thirds of the world
population would be city dwellers. Already straining under the
pressures of meeting their peoples' needs for housing, jobs and
basic services, cities must be also addressing the environmental
and social consequences of rapid urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Annan said cities and towns were engines of progress, the
source of much of the world's cultural, intellectual, educational
and technological achievements and innovations. However, the
stress of rapid urban population growth was often overwhelming,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said that despite growing investments,
more than one third of the urban population were living in
substandard housing and 40 percent of urban dwellers had no access
to safe drinking water or adequate sanitation. These and other
common problems -- such as declining infrastructure, congestion,
pollution and crime -- were not only threatening the economic
potential of cities, but also social cohesion and political
stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said World Habitat Day this year should be an opportunity
for people everywhere to continue looking at how they could
contribute to implementation of the Habitat Agenda -- the
comprehensive blueprint for creating sustainable human settlements
in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
