<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Firmly Against EU Farm Policy Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- German Agriculture Minister Jochen
Bochert today stressed Germany's firm opposition to European Union
(EU) plans to reduce farm subsidies and price supports, saying the
move would cause the income of German farmers to drop by 15 to 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
The plans "would lead to a situation in which our agricultural
producers would be confronted even more strongly by cheaper
producers from outside of the Union," Bochert told the newspaper
Die Welt in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The EU is considering proposals to reduce its set prices for
grain, beef and milk by 10 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Farm subsidies are estimated to account for just under 50
percent of the EU's 90 billion ECU (100 billion U.S. dollar) budget
this year.
</P>
<P>
Bonn has also complained that while Germany was paying 20
billion marks (11 billion dollars) a year for EU agriculture, it
only got back 11 billion marks (6.05 billion dollars) in this
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
