<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Report: 45 Percent of Africans Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. report distributed here
said that 45 percent of Africans are now living in poverty, the
Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 U.N. report on human development said poverty is
posing a serious threat to socio-economic stability on the African
continent, especially in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The African region along with south Asia now emerges as the
worst poverty-stricken spots on the world map, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
In sub-Saharan Africa, per capita share of gross national
product (GNP) dropped to 21 percent on average during 1981-1989
period, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It singled out Gabon as the hardest hit, with the average per
capita income shrinking by 58 percent. Nigeria followed with 50
percent drop and Cote d'Ivoire with 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income in Mozambique and Niger also regressed by 30
percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
In another report, MENA said the number of the poor in Africa
had increased by two-thirds in a span of 15 years between
1970-1985 and is expected to hit 265 million people over the
coming three years.
</P>
<P>
Africa, with a population of 700 million, is the third most
populous continent in the world, after Asia and Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
