<HEADLINE> Portugal Satisfied with Progress in Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Secretary of State
for Foreign Affairs and Cooperation Jose Lamego said today his
government is "satisfied" with the recent progress in the Angolan
Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement to the press here after attending a
meeting of the Joint Commission of the Angolan peace Process.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Lamego said, institutions of national authority
were re-established in two major strategic regions previously
occupied by the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA), namely Negage city of the Uige province in the
north, and Kuango city of the diamond-producing Lunda-Norte
province in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
This, according to the secretary, is a major step forward
toward the peace process, which indicates the wishes by the two
signatories of the Lusaka Peace Accord in 1994 to consolidate
peace.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, as one of the observer countries, he added, is very
"satisfied" with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
Lamego also disclosed that Prime Minister Antonio Guierres
will pay an official visit to Angola on October 20-24. This will
be his first visit to Angola, which is also an important visit
this year.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the visit, Lamego noted, is to pledge
Portugal's support to the Angolan peace process and to enhance
the friendly ties of cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said he was regretted to say that during the
forthcoming visit, the premier cannot meet UNITA chief Jonas
Savimbi as he is not in Luanda.
</P>
<P>
Lamego arrived here today to start a three-day visit in
Angola, which is aimed to make arrangements for Guierres' coming
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
