<HEADLINE> Algeria Rejects Interference in Its Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Algerian Foreign Minister Ahmed
Attaf reiterated here today Algeria's rejection of any attempt to
interfere in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference here today, Attaf said that
circulating reports about prospective foreign interference in
Algeria's internal affairs had "greater media weight rather than
political significance."
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the few voices which call for
internationalization of the Algerian case were isolated voices
which have no impact on the course of events in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian people and government had categorically rejected
any such attempt in this direction, he added.
</P>
<P>
Attaf said that the international community acknowledges the
existence of strong establishments in Algeria capable of handling
the affairs of the state, and that the destiny of the nation is a
matter of concern to the Algerians alone.
</P>
<P>
Several western powers have recently expressed the desire to
internationalize the Algerian case under the pretext of escalated
terrorist acts throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
About 60,000 people have been reportedly killed since the
Algerian government in January 1992 scrapped a general election
dominated by the radical Islamic Salvation Front. 
</P>
