<HEADLINE> W. Nigerian City Put Among "Sustainable Cities" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ibadan, the capital of west
Nigeria's Oyo state, has been selected as one of the 12 cities
worldwide chosen as demonstration projects in the United
Nations-sponsored "sustainable cities program".
</P>
<P>
This was announced today by Nigeria's Minister of Works and
Housing Major-General Abdulkarim Adisa in an address to mark the
World Habitat Day in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the project would practicalize the concept
of sustainable development by finding effective and realistic
solutions to the serious environmental problems facing Ibadan,
the second largest city in west Nigeria next to the national
economic center of Lagos.
</P>
<P>
A replication was being considered for Kano in the north and
Enugu in the south, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, a remedial program tagged Unban
Basic Services (UBS) had also been initiated with the assistance
of the United Nations Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate goal of the program was set at "contributing to
the alleviation of poverty both in terms of income and basic
services, thus reducing the incidence of children at risk," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's largest cities, including Lagos, Ibadan, Onitsha,
Port Harcourt, Kano and Kaduna, had been selected to implement
the UBS program, the minister said, adding that 72 slum areas, at
a rate of 12 slum areas per city, would be rehabilitated over the
five-year period up to 2001.
</P>
<P>
The government had set the goal of promoting awareness on
population problems and the effects of rapid population growth on
development within the frame of the shortest possible time.
</P>
<P>
The government would also ensure that urban families could
have access to low interest housing loans.
</P>
<P>
In the last one year, the minister said, the federal
government staff housing board had disbursed over 25 million
Naira (about 300,000 U.S. Dollars) as housing loans to federal
civil servants at four percent interest rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
