<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Issue New Currency: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian President Negasso
Gidada today announced that the nation will change its currency.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint meeting of the houses of People's
Representatives and Federation, the president said it is high
time the currency is changed.
</P>
<P>
He said, as the Eritrean government which had been using the
Birr currency has recently issued its own currency, this is one
of the factors that reciprocated the change.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of a new currency will avoid problems which
might arise from the launching of the new Eritrean currency, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Gidada said the change is important also because the symbols
that are on the bank notes are not consistent with the
constitution, adding that ''we need symbols and logos that are in
consistence with the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
The necessary measures have been taken to avoid complications
that could occur when the new currency enters into it full force,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The president urged the people to continue to use the Birr
until the new currency is issued, and said the details of the
conversion will be made public soon by the government.
</P>
<P>
The currency Birr which is used in Ethiopia was issued during
the former Mengistu regime. Eritrea announced its independence
from Ethiopia in 1993 and issued its own currency Naqfa last
August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
