<HEADLINE> Israel Has Right to Fight Against Hamas: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel has the right to fight
against the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) at any time in a
bid to protect its civilians from terror attacks, an Israeli
security official said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a news briefing held in the Israeli Government Press Office,
Hared Gadi, a member of the bureau for counter-terrorism in Prime
Minister Office, told reporters that Israel "holds the right to
fight against Hamas, to fight against the terror activities, and
to limit the option of terror activities whenever they are."
</P>
<P>
Gadi's remarks on Hamas indicated that the Israeli government
would not change its stance on fighting terrorism after it allowed
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, founder of the Hamas, to return to the Gaza
Strip and released 20 Palestinian and Jordanian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
"Hamas is an organization, which waves the flag to fight
against Israel in all places without choosing targets. It's
hitting and targeting whenever it is possible when it likes to
do it, never mind it is military or civil target, women or
children," said Gadi, commenting on the recent suicide bombing
attacks in Jerusalem, which killed more than 20 Israeli
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Alluding to the failed attack on Hamas political leader
Khaled Mashal in Amman, Gadi said that Hamas in Jordan has
existed for a long time and all the efforts which have been done
to minimize the Hamas presence in Jordan were not successful.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Hamas in Jordan is not a political party but
headquarters that sends orders, manpower and weaponry to the cells
of Hamas in Israel and tell them when, how and to what limit
to execute terror activities.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the release of Yassin last Wednesday, Gadi said
that his release was arranged "under pressure and due to the
current circumstances." 
</P>
</TEXT>
