<HEADLINE> Minister on Housing Shortage in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Tanzanian
government official has appealed for making greater investment
and implementing birth control policy so as to ease shortage of
housing.
</P>
<P>
The annual supply for housing in Tanzania is 20 percent lower
than demand, Gideon Cheyo, Minister for Lands and Human
Settlement Development, told an international conference which
opens here today.
</P>
<P>
Cheyo said in a speech, read by his deputy Mohamed Mudhihir,
human settlements conditions in developing countries have been
deteriorating because of the little investment in the sector.
</P>
<P>
For example, only 5.6 percent of central government
expenditure in developing countries went to housing, social
security and welfare, compared with 39 percent in developed
nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cheyo said high population growth rate has somehow
contributed to the high demand of housing in many countries,
including Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The growth of population need "proper planning and
management," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that better housing is a pre-condition for
better social life and proper planning can ensure better housing
conditions and sustained development.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attended by 100 participants, is held on
planning legislation, housing and environment in Africa. Similar
conferences have been held in Lesotho, Namibia and South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
