<HEADLINE> Clerides Calls for UN Pressure in Resolving Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Greek Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides today renewed his call on the international
community to help resolve the long-standing Cyprus dispute.
</P>
<P>
"It is with great regret that once again in addressing the
General Assembly, I have to report that no progress has been made
towards the solution of the Cyprus problem due to the
inflexibility of the Turkish side," Clerides said in the general
debate of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He asked the international community to draw attention to the
Cyprus problem and appealed to the U.N. Security Council to use
"all means in its power to persuade the Turkish side to abandon
(its) intransigent position."
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus has been divided
into the North and South since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
the island to protect the Turkish minority following a failed coup
by the Greek military officers allied with the junta then ruling
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been making efforts for a long time for
the peaceful reunification of the island nation. U.N.-brokered
talks between Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
broke down in August after the European Union reaffirmed that it
would begin talks with the Greek-led Cypriot government on EU
membership. Denktash wants Turkey to join the EU too.
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats said that they believe the Greek Cypriots
would offer no new proposals to resolve the dispute until after
the Greek Cypriot presidential elections next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's C. Bank Sells Dollars to Stablize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Angola National Bank has been
selling a large sum of U.S. Dollars twice recently in a bid to
reverse the depreciation of its currency Kwanza.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that due to a recent shortage of foreign
currencies in Angola's monetary market and the local currency,
Readjusted Kwanza has been increasingly depreciating.
</P>
<P>
To reverse the trend, the National Bank dumped 45 million
Dollars on Saturday to its commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The money, which is to be used mainly by industrial sectors,
includes nearly four million Dollars for import substitution of
the industrial products, one million for maize, four million for
animal husbandry, 12 million for industrial development and the
rest for free trade in financial market.
</P>
<P>
Emanuel Carneiro, Minister of Planning, said after the
dollar-sale ceremony, that the Angolan government is working hard
to achieve social and economic stability.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the stability of macro-economy cannot be
obtained without the help of entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose for the Central Bank to sell U.S. Dollars is
to build up an atmosphere of trust so that all Angolans are
confident to participate in the development of national economy.
</P>
<P>
The selling of Dollars this time by the National Bank has
contributed much to stablizing the exchange rate between
Readjusted Kwanza and foreign currencies. Today's exchange rates
between Readjusted Kwanza and major foreign currencies remained
the same level as during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the National Bank will once again sell a
large amount of Dollar on October 10 to further stabilize the
local currency. 
</P>
