<HEADLINE> Three Arrested in US on Charges of Spying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) has arrested three people, including a former
Pentagon attorney, on charges of spying for East Germany and
Russia in the 1970s and 1980s, the U.S. Justice Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
The FBI arrested the three Saturday in the Washington area
after two of them handed classified documents to FBI agents posing
as Russian or South African intelligence officers, it said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Those arrested were: Kurt Alan Stand, 42, of Washington, D.C.,
who works for a union representing food, hotel and other workers;
his wife Theresa Squillacote, 39, who until January was a senior
staff attorney in the office for a deputy undersecretary of
defense; and James Michael Clark, 49, of Falls Church, Virginia,
an investigator with a private firm.
</P>
<P>
The arrested were charged today by a federal judge in the
Virginia town of Alexandria with conspiracy to commit espionage.
</P>
