<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government, KNUT Resume talks on Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government today
resumed talks with the Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT) in
a bid to end the on-going nationwide teachers' strike starting
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government today issued a statement, advising
all teachers currently participating in the illegal strike to
report back to their duty stations by 8:00 a.m. on October 8.
</P>
<P>
The statement signed by Kenyan Education Minister Joseph
Kamotho said those who fail to report to work would be deemed to
have deserted duty and that disciplinary measures would be taken
against such teachers.
</P>
<P>
The teachers who will report for duty as required will not be
victimized for the period they have been on strike, it added.
</P>
<P>
KNUT Secretary General Ambrose Adongo said last week that the
nationwide strike by 200,000 primary and secondary school
teachers would continue until a breakthrough was achieved.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' union is demanding a salary increase ranging
between 150 and 200 percent while the government has agreed to
give a salary increase ranging between 10 and 28 percent plus
allowance increment of between 15 and 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Labor Minister Philip Masinde noted last week that the
government could not meet the demands raised by the union, noting
that the higher salaries would amount to 89 billion Shillings
(about 1.4 billion Dollars) a year, or 56 percent of the total
government revenue.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the Kenyan government could not
reasonably be expected to devote more than half of its budget to
paying teachers.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that teachers are too essential to
relegate them to the periphery of national concerns, in other
words, ways must be found to pay them a decent salary so that
they can function as real professionals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
