<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two-Thirds of States Fail to Meet Child Support Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Two-thirds of the states in
the United States failed to meet a deadline to install computer
systems tracking child support, with one-third facing massive
fines.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a week after the October 1 deadline, 33 state systems
have not been certified as complete by federal inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Of those, 16 states are ready to be certified, said Michael
Kharfen, spokesman for the Department of Health and Human Services
(HHS).
</P>
<P>
That leaves 17 states, representing nearly half the nation's
child support cases, with systems that are not even near
completion.
</P>
<P>
The computerized systems are important because one-third of all
child support cases involve an out-of-state parent, and the
automated systems should help find parents who move from state to
state. They'll also help track in-state cases by making a wealth
of employment and other information about parents available
electronically.
</P>
<P>
States have spent 2.6 billion dollars on the task since 1980,
when Congress agreed to pay for 90 percent of the cost of
computerization.
</P>
<P>
Federal law requires HHS to cut all child support funding to
states without working child support collection systems.
</P>
<P>
In addition, without a working child support system, a state is
also in jeopardy of losing its entire federal welfare grant.
</P>
<P>
No fines are expected until mid-1998, after a series of
reports, reviews and appeals are completed.
</P>
<P>
State officials are reportedly lobbying for a second deadline
extension by Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
