<HEADLINE> Hamas Founder: No Ceasefire with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Founder of the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) Sheikh Ahmad Yassin said here today
that there would be no cease-fire between his group and Israel
until Israel withdrew from all the occupied Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
Yassin made the remarks during the first ever press
conference five days after he was released from Israeli prison
and just before he was flown from here this afternoon in a
Jordanian helicopter to his home in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians refused to stay under occupation and would
do their best in a positive way to "dismiss occupation," said
Yassin, who was allowed to go home after Jordan released two
alleged special agents from Israeli secret service Mossad, who
attempted to kill a Hamas leader here last month.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he had made a call for a cease-fire in Palestinian
attacks against Israelis, he said that "the cease-fire can't be
obtained until the occupation is over."
</P>
<P>
Yassin called on the international community to support the
Palestinians in their efforts to gain their freedom and realize
their dream of an independent homeland.
</P>
<P>
"I would address the whole world and say that we are peace
seekers," he said. "We love peace. And we call on them to
maintain peace with us and to help us in order to restore our
right by means of peace."
</P>
<P>
Yassin was jailed by Israel in 1989 and had been expected to
serve a life sentence for ordering attacks by Hamas guerrilla
against Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
He said that the release of himself was a good and positive
step and a good indicator for the Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations which has been stalled since March this year when
Israel began to build the Har Homa settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is now
one of the only two Arab countries that conceived peace with the
Jewish state. 
</P>
