<HEADLINE> Positive Results in Re-establishing National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Angola's Central Inter-sectoral
Operation Group said today despite some obstacles, the first
phase of re-establishing national authority in areas occupied by
former rebel UNITA movement has produced "positive results".
</P>
<P>
The operation group made the conclusion at a meeting here with
the Joint Commission of the Angolan Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that a total of 101 UNITA-occupied regions
have been handed over to the central government in the first
phase, including 33 cities and 68 towns. Sixty others have not
accomplished the goal as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 37 members of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) have been appointed to the posts
of city mayor or vice mayor, and town chief or deputy chief.
</P>
<P>
Under the program passed by today's meeting, national
authority will be re-established in 172 more areas occupied by
the former rebel movement during the second phase starting
October 11.
</P>
<P>
The operation group believed that with the establishment of
local authority in UNITA-occupied areas, free movement of
personnel and cargo have been improved around the country.
Transport on the country's major highways has resumed to the
normal state. Furthermore, they said, nationwide tension will
disappear and stability will take its place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
