<HEADLINE> GCC Chiefs of Staff Gather for Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Chiefs of Staff from the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) countries gathered in Doha, Qatar
today to attend an annual meeting on strengthening regional
security.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the 15th since the GCC was set up 17 years ago,
took place with a joint GCC naval exercises off the coast of
Bahrain which began Saturday and will last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, dubbed "Solidarity-5", came after Iran bombed
two Iranian rebel bases inside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States said that Iran's air raids violated the
Western allies' no-fly zone over souther Iraq and it warned that
further violations would invite U.S. retaliation.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari news agency said that during the meeting, the GCC
chiefs of staff will discuss the latest developments in the
region, and ways of strengthening GCC member states' defense
capabilities and further boosting military cooperation and
coordination among them.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a political, economic and military alliance, was set
up in 1980. It groups Bahrain, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman
and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War, the GCC states began seeking ways to
strengthen their self-defense capabilities by purchasing advanced
weapons and holding military exercises.
</P>
<P>
However, due to relatively limited human resources, the GCC
countries still remain seriously reliant on a large foreign
presence, particularly that of the U.S. and its western allies
to protect their security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
