<HEADLINE> US: Israel Must Take Consequences of Assassinations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States, irritated
with Israel over a botched assassination attempt on a Hamas
leader, said today that the Jewish state had to take account of
the consequences of its actions.
</P>
<P>
Two agents of the Israeli intelligence service Mossad attacked
Hamas political leader Khaled Meshal in Amman, the Jordanian
capital, on September 25 with a device that stunned him and
injected a poison into him.
</P>
<P>
Meshal's bodyguard and the Jordanian police caught the two
assailants, who were carrying Canadian passports.
</P>
<P>
The botched assassination led to a complex swap, in which
Israel freed Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin last Monday who
then returned to Palestinian-ruled Gaza and Jordan released the
two suspected Israelis agents.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin, avoiding direct
criticism of Israel for such terror-like assassination, suggested
Washington thought the affair had been mishandled.
</P>
<P>
"The Israelis have the obligation to defend their people from
terrorist acts, and we are not in the habit of second guessing
Israel when it comes to her security," he said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
"That said, we believe that Israel must take into account the
repercussions and consequences of any actions it takes in its
fight against terror," he added.
</P>
<P>
While refusing direct comment on the Israeli assassination,
Rubin noted that American agencies were prohibited by U.S. law
from carrying out assassinations. "Therefore we're opposed to
assassinations by other governments as well," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Action Against Global Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today he is convinced that the threat of global warming is
real and carbon emissions must be cut to avoid a catastrophe for
future generations.
</P>
<P>
However, opening a White House conference on global warming,
Clinton said any reduction of green-house gases emissions should
be done through technology changes and rejected any new energy
taxes or other measures to make energy more costly.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attended by scientists, business groups and
environmentalists, was designed to gather support for the
administration's global warming policy.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is intended to sign a treaty on
climate change in Kyoto, Japan, in December while many U.S.
senators and businessmen have launched a campaign in recent weeks
against the move.
</P>
<P>
"I'm convinced that the science for climate change is real,"
Clinton told the conference held at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
"Although we do not know everything, what we do know is more
than enough to warrant action," Clinton said. "It would clearly
be a grave mistake to bury our heads into the sand and think the
issue will go away."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the U.S. must take a leadership role and be
prepared to commit to realistic and binding goals for reducing
heat-trapping greenhouse gases, especially carbon dioxide, from
burning coal and oil.
</P>
<P>
"We must be prepared to commit to realistic and binding goals
on our emissions of greenhouse gases," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"The great majority of the world's climate scientists have
concluded that if we don't cut our emission of greenhouse gases,
temperatures will rise and will disrupt the global climate. In
fact, most scientists say this process has already begun," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the conference said broad patterns of high
temperatures over the last several years were consistent with
computer predictions of global warming.
</P>
<P>
Many scientists have predicted that increased emissions of
"greenhouse gases," such as carbon dioxide from burning of fossil
fuels and other human activities, will trap heat in the atmosphere
and lead to a gradual increase in temperatures.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told the conference the U.S. will ask at the Kyoto
conference for "meaningful, but equitable commitments" from all
nations, but he did not spell out in detail what the U.S. position
would be there.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce said in a recent news release that
mandatory cuts in energy use could cost the U.S. economy 277
billion U.S. dollars a year by the year 2010, and said many
developing countries may remain exempt from the limitations.
</P>
<P>
"The White House should not allow our country to be stampeded,"
the chamber said.
</P>
<P>
In a three full-page advertisement on the Washington Post
today, hundreds of economic and trade organizations signed a call
urging Clinton not to sign the global climate treaty in Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
The call said that the treaty is "really one of the most
potentially damaging economic and trade agreements the U.S. will
ever be asked to sign." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
