<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rains May Relieve Tanzania's Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- After a long spell of
drought, rain has finally started to fall in Tanzania, and it
may relieve the country's drought, observers here say.
</P>
<P>
The current rainfall recorded more than 170 millimeters from 9
am local time on Sunday to 9 am on Monday in Tanga, Zanzibar and
Dar es Salaam combined together, Noel Kamenya, acting
meteorological director general, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Kamenya told reporters that Tanga recorded the highest,
120.0mm, followed by Zanzibar, 40.1 mm. Dar es Salaam has
received 3.0 mm at the airport and 14.0 mm at the port area.
</P>
<P>
The meteorology official explained that the current rain was
caused by disturbance of air over the sea.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he appealed to farmers to plant drought
resistant crops as it is still uncertain whether the rain will
last.
</P>
<P>
Kamenya said the water level in hydro-electrical power
stations remains unclear at present because water levels depend
on the amount of rainfall in key catchment basin.
</P>
<P>
People are waiting for more precipitation to give relief to a
power crisis in the country. Last Friday water level at the main
electricity-generating dam Mtera which fuels the major power
stations, was only 0.63 meters above the minimum level, dropping
to the lowest water level ever in the history.
</P>
<P>
The drought, influenced by the El Nino weather phenomenon
sweeping most of east Africa, has forced power cuts in some areas
of Tanzania which last for up to 15 hours a day and four times a
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Israel to Continue to Fight Terror </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu vowed here this evening that his government
will continue to fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference after a special cabinet meeting,
Netanyahu said terrorism is still prevailing in this region and
the Israeli defense forces and security services will not only
defend the country but also fight against terror.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism must be wiped out and there will be no safe heaven
for terrorism," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu explained his government's success and "failure" in
fighting against terror, and said that the cabinet has decided
to set up a three-member committee to investigate the "failure",
which apparently refers to the failed attack by two agents of the
Israeli security services "Mossad" on Hamas leader Khaled Mashal
last week in Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he would resign after the committee found that
he is responsible for the failure, he shouted angrily that his
"sole responsibility" is to fight terror.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would not conduct any negotiation with
the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), which he described as
the main sources of terror.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet secretariat said this evening in a statement that
the three-member committee will examine all aspects related to
the Amman incident, both prior to, and during its occurrence.
</P>
<P>
The two agents, who conducted a bungled attack on Mashal on
September 25 in Amman and were arrested in Jordan, returned home
today after being released by the Jordanian police.
</P>
<P>
Their release was carried out under a deal reached by Israel
and Jordan, in exchange for Israel's release of Hamas spiritual
leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin and 20 other Hamas members jailed
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu admitted that this failed attack operation has
harmed Israel's relationship with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side will continue to explain further about
Israel's policy of fighting terror to Amman in order to improve
its relations with Jordan, the Israeli prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said that Netanyahu so far does
not want to swallow the bitter outcome of the failed Amman
incident due to his hardline attitude, which would cause more
damage to Israel's international prestige. 
</P>
</TEXT>
