<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief, Cypriot President Discuss Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan had a meeting
today in New York to discuss the Cyprus problem and possible
developments in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus News Agency reported today that in statements to the
press, Clerides said he and Annan examined "where we stand today"
in the Cyprus question and possible developments until
presidential elections in Cyprus scheduled for February 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president said he and Annan discussed a visit to
Cyprus by the secretary-general's special sdvisor on the Cyprus
problem, Diego Cordovez, but he added it is up to Cordovez to
decide the timing of his visit.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Manolis Christofides, who
accompanies Clerides, said Cordovez was likely to visit the island
in November.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez sponsored two rounds of peace talks between Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in July and August.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the U.N. chief agreed to appoint a new third
member to the U.N. Investigatory Committee for Missing Persons in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Both Clerides and Denktash called on Annan to appoint a new
third member in an agreement to exchange information on the
missing reached in Nicosia in July.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Investigatory Committee for Missing Persons in
Cyprus was set up in 1981 and comprises of a Greek and a Turkish
Cypriot representative and a third member appointed by the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. representative in the committee, Paul Wurth of the
International Red Cross Society, retired in 1996 and has not been
replaced since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
