<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Declines Comment on Israel's Failed Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Monday declined any comment on a botched assassination by the
Israeli intelligence service Mossad on a Hamas leader, only
saying U.S. policy forbids political assassinations.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came after two Mossad agents were arrested in
Amman, the Jordanian capital, on Sept. 25 when they were attacking
Hamas political leader Khaled Meshal with a device that stunned
him and injected a poison into him.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of the United States for our own conduct is and
has been I believe for more than 20 years, under presidents of
both parties, that we do not engage in assassinations," Clinton
told reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
But when asked what was his comment on the failed Israeli
assassination, the president said: "Since the government of
Israel and the government of Jordan have made no comment about
this, I think it is inappropriate for me to make any comment."
</P>
<P>
"I can make no comment on what others did or did not do when
it had not been confirmed by either of the governments in
question," he added.
</P>
<P>
The botched assassination led to a complex swap in which,
Israel freed Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin last Monday who
then returned to Palestinian-ruled Gaza and Jordan released the
two suspected Israeli agents.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also avoided direct
criticism of Israel for such political assassination and
suggested that Washington thought the affair had been midhandled.
</P>
<P>
"The Israelis have the obligation to defend their people from
terrorist acts, and we are not ...the habit of second guessing
Israel when it comes to her security," he said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
"That said, we believe that Israel must take into account the
repercussions and consequences of any actions it takes in its
fight against terror," he added.
</P>
<P>
While refusing direct comment on the Israeli assassination,
Rubin noted that American agencies were prohibited by U.S. law
from carrying out assassinations. "Therefore we're opposed to
assassinations by other governments as well," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
