<HEADLINE> International Community Urged to be Actively </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides today urged the international community to be more
actively involved in efforts for a Cyprus settlement, Cyprus News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the U.N. General Assembly in New York, the
president said that "it is with great regret that once again I
have to report that no progress has been made toward the
solution of the Cyprus problem due to the inflexibility of the
Turkish side."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side, Clerides explained, refused to discuss the
substance of the problem during the latest round of U.N. talks
unless the European Union freezes plans for accession
negotiations with the government of the Republic of Cyprus in
accordance with its decision in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The clear conclusion to be drawn is that more active
involvement of the international community is needed, if talks
are to produce results," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Clerides expressed his firm resolve to secure the country's
defense and take decisions on its arms programs.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to make it abundantly clear that we cannot and will
not relinquish our inalienable right to defend our country and
decide about our armaments," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the Turkish threat emanating from the continued
aggression and occupation of 37 per cent of the territory of the
Republic exists, we have not only the right but also the duty to
provide for the security of the people of Cyprus," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over
the northern third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
