<HEADLINE> Kagame in Kinshasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Vice President Paul
Kagame arrived in Kinshasa today for his first visit to the
Democratic Republic of Congo to discuss the refugees issue, a
U.N. DHA release quoted Congo's state television as saying today.
</P>
<P>
An informed source in the Congolese capital said Kagame, who
led the mainly Tutsi Rwandan Patriotic Front to power in Kigali
in 1994, was to discuss the border situation with President L.
Kabila, who assumed power in May backed by Rwandan troops as
Kagame admitted.
</P>
<P>
Kagame made a brief statement in Kinshasa, saying he would
hold talks on "common problems to find solutions," notably
regarding tension arising from clashes between Rwandan troops and
Hutu rebels near the border and their repercussions for "the
situation in Goma (in eastern Congo) and other concerns."
</P>
<P>
Congolese Interior Minister Mwenze Kongolo announced yesterday
Congo (K) had found over 1,000 heavily-armed soldiers of the
former Rwandan Hutu-dominated army and their Interahamwe militia
allies in Equateur Province in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the soldiers were near
Mbandaka and holding an unspecified number of Rwandan refugees as
hostages.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo added that they were dangerous and military action
would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
Earlier yesterday, Congo's Interior Ministry announced the
closure of its border with Rwanda, and the expulsion of more than
4,000 Rwandan refugees. And it also ordered the staff of the U.N.
refugees agency out of Goma in the eastern part of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
