<HEADLINE> U.S. Condemns Hamas while Avoiding Criticism of Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States, while
avoiding criticizing Israel for its failed political
assassination, on Monday condemned Hamas as a "terrorist"
organization and demanded the Palestinian Authority to dismantle
its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Hamas remained "an enemy of peace (and) we are opposed to
Hamas for that reason and believe it is essential for its
terrorist infrastructure to be dismantled," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the botched assassination of Hamas leader
Khaled Meshal in the Jordian capital of Amman on Sept. 25, by
two agents of the Israeli intelligence service Mossad, Rubin
took care not to make any direct criticism.
</P>
<P>
"The Israelis have the obligation to defend their people from
terrorist acts, and we are not in the habit of second guessing
Israel when it comes to her security," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman just made remark in a very general term about
Israel's actions, saying Israel had to take the consequences of
any actions it had taken against the Palestinian organization.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Israel must take into account the
repercussions and consequences of any actions it takes in its
fight against terror," he said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Rubin was seeking to walk a line between U.S.
rock-solid support for Israel and its policies opposed to
terrorism, and to Hamas and to political assassination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
