<HEADLINE> Turkey's Islamic Party Vows to Fight for Survival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's pro-Islamic Welfare
Party (RP) vowed today that it will continue its struggle
against the call for its closure, according to the Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press following the submission of RP's final
written defense to the Constitutional Court, RP parliamentary
group Deputy Chairman Temel Karamollaoglu said that it is
unreasonable to close RP, a legally established party.
</P>
<P>
Only those parties which are involved in unlawful actions
could be banned, Karamollaoglu said. He called on the
Constitutional Court to make a just decision on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"It should not be forgotten that those who pass judgement
will also one day be judged by history," the RP official noted.
</P>
<P>
RP submitted its final written defense to the court today,
the last day of the 30-day extension granted by the supreme
judicial body.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas filed a case with the
Constitutional Court in May demanding the closure of the
pro-Islamic RP on grounds that the RP, led by former prime
minister Necmettin Erbakan, had been encouraging the
fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan and his party had long been criticized for their
reluctance to take tough measures against the rapidly growing
fundamentalists in the secular republic.
</P>
<P>
The RP is now preparing to make its verbal statement to the
court on a certain date to be determined by the Constitutional
Court.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkey's Party Law, Erbakan and some RP
officials will be banned from engaging in politics for at least
five years if the party is outlawed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Erbakan threatened that he would apply to the
European Court of Human Rights if the RP was closed on grounds of
anti-secularism charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
