<HEADLINE> Turkish President: Northern Iraq Used As </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said today that northern Iraq has been used as a
terrorist base against Turkey, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on flight to Kuwait for a two-day
official visit, Demirel said outlawed Turkish militants are
making use of the uncontrolled area to threaten Turkey's border
security.
</P>
<P>
However, some Arab countries will protest loudly when the
Turkish troops enter northern Iraq to crack down on the outlawed
militants, he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has frequently launched military operations in northern
Iraq in the past two years to strike the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) bases.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by jets and
artillery fire, entered northern Iraq to attack the PKK camps,
touching off severe protest from the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran and some Arab countries said that Turkey's action
inviolated Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity, urging
immediate withdrawal of Turkish troops from the region.
</P>
<P>
An earlier Turkish Foreign Ministry statement said that the
Turkish military had the right to do so if they thought it was
necessary, adding that the ongoing operation was only "a limited
and routine one."
</P>
<P>
More than 140 PKK rebels were killed in the latest Turkish
military incursion in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting the Turkish government since 1984
in an attempt to establish an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
