<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Rejects Cyprus' Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash today rejected a proposal by the Cypriot government on
a partial lifting of trade embargo against Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said that the Cypriot government's recent proposal to
have limited trade with Turkish Cypriots was a game aimed at
facilitating Cyprus' accession to the European Union (EU), the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under this proposal, Turkish Cypriots' products have to be
approved by the Cypriot government, Denktash said, adding this
would mean a Greek Cypriots' influence in northern part of the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into Greek Cypriot South and Turkish
Cypriot North since 1974 when Turkey sent troops to the island
and took over the northern third of the eastern Mediterranean
island.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey, which has
deployed 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has been prohibiting its companies
from having trade relations with Turkish Cypriots and also
Turkey, a political, economic and military supporter of Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Cypriot government's proposal as meaningless,
Denktash stressed that Turkish Cypriots must strengthen their
relations with Turkey if they wants to defend their own interests.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots have been criticizing the Cypriot government's
plan to become an EU member country, saying it cannot represent
the interests of the Turkish Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
