<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heroic Welcome Greets Hamas Leader's Return to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- About 50,000 cheering
Palestinians in Gaza today extended a heroic welcome to Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin, the founder and spiritual leader of the radical
Islamic group Hamas, upon his return home.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, 61 and wheel chair-bound, was flown from Jordanian
capital Amman this afternoon in a Jordanian military helicopter
to a tumultuous welcome by cheering Palestinian residents and
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) officials in the packed Gaza
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Posters and freshly painted slogan in the walls of buildings
congratulated the return of Yassin, who has been imprisoned by
Israel for nine years and was released to Jordan only last week
in a prisoner exchange deal reached between Israel and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat and his wife Soha were conspicuous
at the welcome ceremony waiting for Yassin's arrival. Arafat's
spokesman Marwan Kanafani told reporters that the PNA was pleased
with the return of the Hamas leader to his home in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
He said that the PNA hoped that Yassin would join efforts to
strive to establish a Palestinian state with East Jerusalem as
its capital. He added that the PNA is continuing dialogue with
not only Hamas but also other opposition groups in order to
achieve this goal.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Yassin's return to Gaza was a political
boost to the militant group and was in fact an awkward moment for
Arafat and the PNA, which had been kept in the dark over the deal
on releasing Yassin. Arafat has failed in his repeated attempts
to secure the release of Yassin in a bid to rein in the most
powerful opposition group in the territories.
</P>
<P>
And the popular Hamas leader's return is expected to increase
the difficulty for Arafat to conduct his ongoing crackdown on
the militant group that has been launching terror attacks
against Israel aimed at derailing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Yassin's release was reportedly part of a deal to release the
two alleged special agents from Israeli secret service Mossad,
who were detained for attempting to assassinate Hamas leader in
Jordan Khaled Mashal.
</P>
<P>
The two agents, holding forged Canadian passports, were
arrested after they attacked Mashal outside his Amman office and
injected poison into his face. But Mashal survived after being
treated in hospital, and the incident caused extensive damages
to the relations between Israel and both Jordan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said Netanyahu had personally ordered the
attack against Mashal because he was considered to be the No.1
in the Hamas, who often gives orders to launch suicide bombing
attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was responsible for the July 30 twin suicide bombings in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market and the September 4 triple
bombings in the Ben Yehuda pedestrian mall, which killed 25
people and wounded over 300 others.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before Yassin's arrival in Gaza, the two Israeli
agents returned to Israel under the Israeli-Jordannia deal. And
20 prisoners, 11 Palestinians and nine Jordanians, were released
from Israeli prisons apparently as part of the prisoner
swap. Israel Radio reported that 50 more Palestinian prisoners,
who were not involved in murders, would also be freed from jails
within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Hussein reportedly spoke with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu by phone this afternoon to
discuss Yassin's return to Gaza and the prisoner exchange, but
the Prime Minister's Office here denied the reports.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, who held a chaotic news conference before leaving
Amman, vowed to carry on Hamas' fight against Israel until the
end of Israeli occupation. He stressed that Israel must
recognize the rights of the Palestinians' return to their
homeland and release all Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas leader also called for the unity among all
Palestinians, as well as between Hamas and the PNA, in order to
fight for the establishment of a Palestinian state with East
Jerusalem as its capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
