<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, PNA Announce Resumption of Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- After nearly seven months'
deadlock, the Israeli-Palestinian peace process will be formally
resumed Tuesday, Israeli and Palestinian officials announced here
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Following a two-hour meeting between Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) deputy head
Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) here in the Laromme Hotel which was
attended by United States special peace envoy Dennis Ross, the
two sides announced to revive the negotiations of the nine joint
committees created to discuss the implementation of the Interim
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight's meeting ...is the expression of mutual desire to
continue in our efforts to make progress to our mutual goal,
goal of peace between us," Levy told a tripartite news
conference held with Mazen and Ross after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that the two sides would make determined efforts to
advance the issues concerning the implementation of the Interim
Agreement in order to reach an agreement. He stressed that the
need to fight terrorism in order to create the atmosphere needed
to make progress.
</P>
<P>
"Our determination to advance the issues, to proceed, is also
intended to create the necessary atmosphere which stands firm in
opposition to terrorism, and our work together is giving
expression to that strong opposition against terror and create
the atmosphere needed for making peace between us," Levy added.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Mazen expressed appreciation for the role
played by the U.S. administration in bringing the two sides back
to negotiating table after the prolonged deadlock.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process has been off the track for a long time,
and I say now it's time to revive it," he said, promising that
the PNA would honor its commitments to fighting terrorism in
order to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, I would reiterate our commitments to
activate our coordination and cooperation in all spheres,
including security sphere, and our efforts to combat violence
and terror, which are committed to Israelis and Palestinians,"
Mazen added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that both sides would discuss the urgent issues,
especially the "unilateral steps" taken by Israel, including the
settlement activities, confiscation of Palestinian land, and
demolition of Palestinian homes and revocation of ID cards of
Palestinian residents in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"These issues constitute the basic principles and fundamental
basis to revive the peace process, and to give the peace process
a chance it deserves," Mazen said.
</P>
<P>
He demanded Israel implement the signed agreements according
to the prinicples stipulated by United National resolutions 242
and 338, and the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of the agreements on the ground will be
the only way to revive and restore the confidence and
credibility to the peace process," Mazen said.
</P>
<P>
Tonight's meeting was convened according to the agreement
reached late September in Washington by Levy and Mazen to break
the prolonged peace deadlock caused by Israel's building of the
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem since March.
</P>
<P>
After initial talks here, the negotiations are expected to
shift to Washington to continue the efforts to reach
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971007.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Investigate Total's Deal with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States is sending
experts to France, Russia and Malaysia as part of a U.S. probe to
determine if sanctions should be imposed in connection with their
companies' 2 billion US dollars natural gas deal with Iran, the
State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to be sending experts to the three countries to
investigate and talk with officials in those countries about the
terms of these contracts as part of the work that we need to do to
make a determination of whether sanctionable activity has taken
place or will take place," State Department spokesman James Rubin
said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to anticipate the results of our review or
speculate about what decisions we will make," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States launched the investigation after the Total
Oil Group of France and its Russian and Malaysian coalition
partners announced on Sept.29 that they, defying threat from
Washington of imposing sanctions, had concluded the $2 billion
deal with Iran to develop Iran's vast South Pars natural gas
field, which is expected to produce 20 billion cubic meters of
natural gas a year.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1996 Iran-Libya Sanctions Act, President Bill Clinton
is required to impose sanctions on any foreign company investing
more than 20 million dollars a year in the two countries, energy
industries.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told reporters that "no decision has been made concerning
the imposition of sanctions" under the act. But he indicated
Washington might waive the sanctions if European governments agree
to increase pressure on Iran, which Washington alleged to have
supported "terrorism".
</P>
<P>
However, members of the European Union have threatened to file
a complaint with the World Trade Organization if the United States
tries to impose such sanctions.
</P>
<P>
EU trade chief Leon Brittan warned the United States at a
meeting at Luxembourg on Monday that meddling in European trade
affairs could lead to counter-sanctions and the 15 EU nations
unanimously backed the $2 billion natural gas deal.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said the EU would take the case to the WTO by Oct. 15
unless there was substantial progress on resolving the dispute.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans are entitled to disagree with Us," Brittan said.
"What they are not entitled to do is to impose their will."
</P>
</TEXT>
